## Chapter 29: Interest-Rate Futures Contracts

### Introduction to Futures

- **Futures contract**: agreement requiring party to buy/sell something at designated future date at predetermined price
- Interest-rate futures, options, and swaps covered in chapters 29-31
- Derivatives enable proactive portfolio risk management — alter interest-rate sensitivity economically and quickly
- Offer risk/return patterns previously unavailable or too costly

### Mechanics of Futures Trading

- **Futures price**: price at which parties agree to transact in future
- **Settlement/delivery date**: designated date when transaction must occur
- Settlement dates typically March, June, September, December
- **Nearby futures contract**: nearest settlement date
- **Most distant futures contract**: furthest from settlement
- **Long position (long futures)**: buyer of futures contract
- **Short position (short futures)**: seller of futures contract

### Liquidating Positions

- Two liquidation options: (1) offset position before settlement, or (2) wait until settlement date
- Offsetting: buyer sells identical contracts; seller buys identical contracts
- At settlement: buyer accepts delivery at agreed price; seller delivers at agreed price
- **Cash-settlement contracts**: some futures settle in cash only (no physical delivery)

### Role of Clearinghouse

- Clearinghouse guarantees both parties will perform — eliminates counterparty risk
- Takes opposite position to every trade
- Investors free to liquidate without involving original counterparty or worrying about default
- Simplifies unwinding positions — no need to negotiate with original party
- **Bob & Sally example**: clearinghouse intermediates bond XYZ futures, enabling either party to exit by trading identical contract

### Margin Requirements

- **Initial margin**: minimum deposit per contract specified by exchange (can be interest-bearing Treasury bill)
- Position marked to market daily using settlement price — gains/losses reflected in equity account
- **Maintenance margin**: minimum equity level before additional margin required
- **Variation margin**: additional cash deposit to restore equity to initial margin level (must be cash, not securities)
- Excess margin withdrawable by investor
- Failure to deposit variation margin within 24 hours → position closed out
- Margin for futures = "good faith" money (not borrowed funds like securities margin)

### Futures vs. Forward Contracts

- **Forward contract**: agreement for future delivery at specified price, usually nonstandard/negotiated
- No clearinghouse for forwards — **counterparty risk** exists (risk other party fails to perform)
- Forwards typically intended for delivery; futures generally not (less than 2% settled by delivery)
- Forwards may/may not be marked to market
- Forwards expose parties to credit risk; futures have minimal credit risk due to clearinghouse guarantee
- Both futures and forwards subject to interim cash flows (margin requirements), but variation margin treatment differs

### Risk and Return Characteristics

- Buyer profits if futures price increases; seller profits if price decreases
- **Example**: futures price rises $100 → $120, buyer gains $20; seller loses $20
- **Example**: futures price falls $100 → $40, buyer loses $60; seller gains $60

### Leveraging Aspect

- Only initial margin required, not entire investment amount
- **Example**: $100 investment with $5 initial margin allows purchase of 20 contracts (ignoring variation margin)
- Payoff depends on 20 bonds, not one — leverages funds
- Leverage varies by contract, considerably greater than cash market
- Leverage enables futures to reduce price risk at reasonable cost for many participants

### Interest-Rate Futures Exchanges

- Two major U.S. exchanges: **Chicago Mercantile Exchange (CME)** and **NYSE Euronext**
- Both offer short-term products: Eurodollar futures (U.S. LIBOR), SOFR futures, EURIBOR futures
- Treasury futures: 2-year, 5-year, 10-year notes; 30-year bonds; **ultra Treasury bond futures** (for managing long-term interest rates)
- Contract specifications cover: deliverable grades, price quotation, tick size, contract months, last trading day, last delivery day, delivery method

### Eurodollar Futures

- Traded on CME's International Monetary Market and London International Financial Futures Exchange
- **Underlying**: Eurodollar time deposit with $1 million principal, 3 months to maturity
- One of most heavily traded futures in world
- Frequently used to trade short end of yield curve — "best hedging vehicle for wide range of hedging situations"
- Interest rate: **LIBOR (London Interbank Offered Rate)** — add-on interest rate
- Parties agree to buy/sell "3-month LIBOR"

### Eurodollar Futures Pricing

- Quoted on **index price basis**: 100 minus annualized futures 3-month LIBOR
- **Example**: index price 94.52 → 3-month LIBOR = 5.48% (100 - 94.52)
- **Principal**: $1 million
- **One tick**: 0.01 index price change
- One-tick change = 1-basis-point (0.0001) change in 3-month LIBOR
- One tick = $25 value change: $1,000,000 × (0.0001 × 90/360) = $25
- 10-tick change = $250 value change
- **Minimum price fluctuation**: half tick ($12.50) normally; quarter tick ($6.25) in nearest trading month
- Contracts listed for March, June, September, December ("March cycle"), plus 40 months in March quarterly cycle and four nearest serial months
- Positions can extend out 10 years

### Eurodollar Settlement Example

- **Cash settlement contract**: settles in cash based on 3-month LIBOR
- **Example**: trade at 94.52, settlement index 95.00 → index increased 0.48
- Buyer receives 48 ticks × $25 = $1,200 from seller
- Alternative interpretation: buyer contracted for 5.42% rate (100.00 - 94.52), market rate 5.00% → compensation for lower prevailing rate

### Eurodollar Hedging Application

- Protect against rising borrowing costs six months out
- Take position benefiting from short-term rate rise (short position = sell futures)
- **Example**: 3-month LIBOR rises 5.48% → 6.00%, settlement index 94.00
- Seller sold at 94.52, purchased at 94.00 → gain of 0.52 or 52 ticks
- Buyer pays seller $1,300 (52 × $25)
- Gain offsets higher borrowing costs from rate increase

### LIBOR Transition to SOFR

- LIBOR being phased out as reference rate
- CME proposed November 2019 plan to convert Eurodollar futures/options to SOFR reference rate
- **Fallback trigger**: contingency plan to make Eurodollar futures a SOFR futures with same expiration month
- Futures price would be pre-fallback Eurodollar price plus spread adjustment

### SOFR Futures

- Introduced April 2018: (1) **1-month SOFR futures (SR1)**, (2) **3-month SOFR futures (SR3)**
- Cash-settlement contracts
- Among fastest-growing new products in CME history
- **SOFR (Secured Overnight Financing Rate)**: cost of borrowing cash overnight using Treasury securities as collateral
- Single backward-looking rate for actual transactions (not forward-looking like LIBOR)
- SOFR is overnight rate; LIBOR is expected 3-month future rate
- Taking position in SOFR futures = taking view on what SOFR will be over time period (view on average SOFR)

### 3-Month SOFR Futures Mechanics

- More actively traded of the two SOFR contracts
- **Contract unit**: *compounded* daily SOFR interest during Reference Quarter
- **Reference Quarter**: interval from third Wednesday of third month preceding delivery month
- Quarterly contracts: March, June, September, December for 39 consecutive quarters
- Compounded daily SOFR used (not single value) because SOFR is overnight rate and 3-month SOFR sought

### SOFR Futures Pricing Formula

- Given compounded SOFR → calculate **Contract IMM Index**:
  - Contract IMM Index = 100 - Compounded SOFR during Reference Quarter
- Given Contract IMM Index → calculate **contract unit**:
  - Contract unit = Contract IMM Index × $2,500
- **Example**: compounded SOFR in Reference Quarter = 1.92% (0.0192)
  - Contract IMM Index = 100 - 1.92 = 98.08
  - Contract unit = 98.08 × $2,500 = $245,200
- **Basis point value**: $25 per contract (1-basis-point change in compounded SOFR)
- **Example**: 1.93% vs 1.92% → Contract IMM Index 98.07 → contract unit $245,175 (decline of $25)

### 1-Month SOFR Futures

- Uses average daily SOFR during futures contract delivery month (simple average, not compounded)
- Contract IMM Index formula same as 3-month version
- Contract unit = Contract IMM Index × $4,167
- **Basis point value**: $41.67 per 1-month SOFR futures (vs. $25 for 3-month)

### EURIBOR Futures

- **EURIBOR (European Interbank Offered Rate)**: rate at which Eurozone banks lend unsecured funds to each other
- Interbank rate like LIBOR
- Commitment to pay/receive quarterly interest payment on settlement date based on 3-month EURIBOR
- Cash settlement contract
- Quoted on index-price basis: 100 minus annualized futures reference rate (EURIBOR-based)
- **Example**: EURIBOR futures price 94.00 → futures 3-month EURIBOR = 6%
- **Minimum price fluctuation (tick)**: 0.005 (or 0.00005 in EURIBOR terms)
- **Basis point value**: €12.50

### Treasury Futures Overview

- Most active bond derivatives contracts
- Classified by maturity: **Treasury bond futures** (coupon securities originally issued as bonds), **Treasury note futures** (2-year, 5-year, 10-year)

### Treasury Bond Futures Contract

- **Underlying**: $100,000 par value hypothetical 20-year 6% coupon bond
- **Futures price quoted**: par being 100, in 32nds of 1%
- **Example**: quote 97-16 means 97 and 16/32, or 97.50% of par → $97,500 for $100,000 par
- **Minimum price fluctuation**: 1/32 of 1% → $31.25 for $100,000 par value

### Delivery Options in Treasury Bond Futures

- Not cash settlement — seller can make delivery (but most liquidate, not deliver)
- Seller delivers actual Treasury bond, but which one?
- CME Group allows seller to deliver one of several Treasury bonds exchange declares acceptable
- Bonds seller can select published by exchange before trading begins for specific settlement date
- **Eligible issues criteria**: minimum 15 years to maturity from delivery date if not callable; if callable, not callable for at least 15 years from first day of delivery month
- Newly issued Treasury bonds also qualify

### Conversion Factors

- **Problem**: delivering different acceptable bonds creates fairness issues
  - Delivering 5% 20-year bond vs. 7% 20-year bond creates value imbalance
- **Solution**: CME Group introduces **conversion factors** to equalize delivery
- Conversion factor determined before contract trading begins with specific settlement date
- Conversion factor constant throughout trading period for given settlement month
- Short must notify long of actual bond delivered one day before delivery date

### Invoice Price

- **Invoice price**: settlement futures price plus accrued interest on bonds delivered
- Seller can deliver one of several acceptable Treasury issues
- Invoice price adjusted based on actual Treasury issue delivered using conversion factors
- **Formula**: invoice price = contract size × futures contract settlement price × conversion factor + accrued interest

### Invoice Price Example

- Treasury bond futures settles at 94-08; short delivers bond with conversion factor 1.20
- Settlement price 94-08 = 94.25% of par
- Contract size $100,000
- Invoice price = $100,000 × 0.9425 × 1.20 + accrued interest = $113,100 + accrued interest

### Cheapest-to-Deliver Issue

- Short selects from all deliverable issues the one **cheapest to deliver**
- Key role in pricing futures contract
- Determined by participants
<!-- pp. 1001-1020 -->

## Chapter 29: Interest-Rate Futures Contracts (continued)

### Implied Repo Rate and Cheapest-to-Deliver

- **Implied repo rate**: Return earned by buying an acceptable Treasury issue and delivering it at the futures settlement date
- Seller calculates this knowing current Treasury price and agreed futures price
- **Cheapest-to-deliver issue**: The acceptable Treasury with the highest implied repo rate — gives seller the highest return by buying and delivering
- Short position evaluates all acceptable issues to identify cheapest-to-deliver

### Delivery Options for Short Position

**Quality option (swap option)**:
- Short chooses which acceptable Treasury issue to deliver
- Affects futures pricing — introduces uncertainty for long position

**Timing option**:
- Short decides when in the delivery month to actually deliver
- Delivery can occur any time during the month

**Wild card option**:
- Right to give notice of intent to deliver up to 8:00 PM Chicago time (after 3:15 PM exchange close)
- Provides additional flexibility to short position

> These three options collectively called **delivery options** mean the long position never knows which bond will be delivered or when

### Ultra Treasury Bond Futures

- **Deliverable**: Bond with maturity of at least 25 years
- Otherwise identical specifications to Treasury bond futures
- Effectively creates **long maturity bond futures contract** for managing the long end of yield curve
- Treasury bond futures = short maturity contract; Ultra Treasury = long maturity contract
- Better suited for managing duration of long-term bond portfolios

### Treasury Note Futures Contracts

**10-year Treasury note futures**:
- Underlying: $100,000 par value hypothetical 10-year 6% Treasury note
- Acceptable delivery: Maturity 6.5 to 10 years from first day of delivery month
- Same delivery options and minimum price fluctuations as Treasury bond futures

**5-year Treasury note futures**:
- Underlying: $100,000 par value U.S. Treasury note
- Original maturity: Not more than 5 years 3 months
- Remaining maturity: No greater than 5 years 3 months
- Remaining maturity: Not less than 4 years 3 months

**2-year Treasury note futures**:
- Underlying: $200,000 par value
- Remaining maturity: Not more than 2 years, not less than 1 year 9 months
- Original maturity: Cannot exceed 5 years 2 months

### Pricing and Arbitrage in Interest-Rate Futures

**Market efficiency concerns**:
- Buyers worry prices are too high — manipulated by experienced traders
- Sellers worry prices are artificially low — bargain-basement levels
- Violent ups and downs in leveraged futures markets create losses
- Efficient market theories provide little comfort given sudden losses possible

**Reality**:
- Futures markets not perfectly efficient, but come close
- Clear reasons why futures prices are what they are
- Methods exist for traders/investors/borrowers to quickly eliminate discrepancies
- Multiple approaches to price futures contracts, all converging on same fair price via **law of one price**

### Theoretical Futures Pricing

**Law of one price**:
- Financial asset must have same price regardless of how it's created
- Futures contracts can combine with cash instruments to create identical cash flows to other securities
- Synthetically created securities must have same price as actual securities
- Cash instruments can combine to create cash flows identical to futures contracts
- By law of one price, futures must have same price as synthetic futures from cash instruments

**Cash-and-carry arbitrage example**:
- 20-year 100-par bond, 12% coupon, selling at par
- Bond deliverable for futures contract settling in 3 months
- Current 3-month interest rate: 8% per year
- If futures price is 107:
  - Sell futures at 107
  - Purchase bond for 100
  - Borrow 100 for 3 months at 8%
  - Outcome: Total proceeds 110 (bond 107 + accrued interest 3), total outlay 102 (repay 100 + interest 2), **profit = 8**
- Profit realized **regardless of futures price at settlement date**
- Arbitrageurs would buy bond and sell futures, forcing futures price down

**Reverse cash-and-carry arbitrage**:
- If futures price is 92:
  - Buy futures at 92
  - Sell (short) bond for 100
  - Invest (lend) 100 for 3 months at 8%
  - Outcome: Total outlay 95 (bond 92 + accrued 3), total proceeds 102 (principal 100 + interest 2), **profit = 7**
- Pure arbitrage profit with no initial cash outlay, realized regardless of settlement price

**No-arbitrage price**:
- At futures price of 99, both strategies yield zero profit
- Therefore **99 is the theoretical futures price** — any higher or lower permits arbitrage

### Theoretical Futures Price Formula

**Variables**:
- *r* = financing rate (borrowing/lending rate)
- *c* = current yield (coupon rate ÷ cash market price)
- *P* = cash market price
- *F* = futures price
- *t* = time in years to futures delivery date

**Equilibrium condition**:
- Profit from cash-and-carry = 0
- 0 = *F* + *ctP* − (*P* + *rtP*)

**Solving for theoretical futures price**:
$$F = P[1 + t(r - c)]$$ (Equation 29.1)

**Example application**:
- *r* = 0.08, *c* = 0.12, *P* = 100, *t* = 0.25
- *F* = 100[1 + 0.25(0.08 − 0.12)] = 99
- Confirms theoretical price derived from arbitrage arguments

### Net Financing Cost and Carry

**Net financing cost**: (*r* − *c*) — adjusts financing rate for coupon interest earned
- Also called **cost of carry** or simply **carry**

**Positive carry** (*c* > *r*):
- Current yield earned > financing cost
- Futures will sell at discount to cash price (*F* < *P*)

**Negative carry** (*c* < *r*):
- Financing cost > current yield
- Futures will sell at premium to cash price (*F* > *P*)

**Zero carry** (*c* = *r*):
- Futures equal to cash price (*F* = *P*)

**Interest-rate futures and yield curve shape**:
- When yield curve is upward sloping: short-term financing rate generally < current yield on bond → positive carry
- Futures price sells at discount to cash price for bond
- When yield curve inverted: opposite holds true

### Assumptions and Implications

**Interim cash flows**:
- Model assumes no variation margin or coupon payments during futures contract life
- Price derived is technically for **forward contract** (not marked-to-market daily)
- Rising interest rates: short position receives margin, can reinvest at higher rate
- Falling interest rates: variation margin must be financed by short at lower cost
- Whoever way rates move, shorts gain relative to longs (forwards vs. futures difference)

**Incorporating coupon payments**:
- Not difficult, but value at settlement depends on reinvestment rate
- Shorter maturity and lower coupon rate → less important reinvestment income for determining futures price

**Short-term interest rate differences**:
- Model assumes borrowing rate (*r_B*) = lending rate (*r_L*)
- Reality: borrowing rate typically > lending rate
- Creates boundaries for theoretical futures price:
  - Upper boundary: *F* = *P*[1 + *t*(*r_B* − *c*)] (Equation 29.2)
  - Lower boundary: *F* = *P*[1 + *t*(*r_L* − *c*)] (Equation 29.3)

**Example with rate spread**:
- Borrowing rate 8%, lending rate 6%
- Upper boundary: $100[1 + 0.25(0.08 − 0.12)] = $99
- Lower boundary: $100[1 + 0.25(0.06 − 0.12)] = $98.50
- Transaction costs also affect boundaries

**Deliverable bond uncertainty**:
- Model assumes only one deliverable instrument
- Treasury bonds/notes allow short to choose from multiple deliverable issues (**quality/swap option**)
- Market participants track each deliverable bond's price to determine **cheapest-to-deliver**
- Cheapest-to-deliver can change over time, dramatically altering futures price

**Quality option impact on pricing**:
- Quality option = option granted by long to short
- Long will pay less for futures than equation (29.1) indicates
- Adjusted formula: *F* = *P*[1 + *t*(*r* − *c*)] − value of quality option (Equation 29.4)
- Theoretical models exist to estimate fair value of quality option

**Timing and wild card options**:
- Short has timing option (when to deliver in month) and wild card option (late notice)
- Long doesn't know when securities will be delivered
- Reduces theoretical futures price below equation (29.1):
  - *F* = *P*[1 + *t*(*r* − *c*)] − quality option value − timing option value − wildcard option value (Equation 29.5)
  - Or: *F* = *P*[1 + *t*(*r* − *c*)] − delivery options (Equation 29.6)

**Index futures and basket arbitrage**:
- Municipal index futures = cash settlement based on basket of securities
- Arbitraging is expensive — can't buy/sell every bond in index
- Smaller portfolio constructed to "track" the index
- Arbitrage no longer risk-free due to **tracking error risk**

## Bond Portfolio Management Applications

### Controlling Portfolio Duration

**Duration adjustment using futures**:
- Portfolio managers with strong interest-rate expectations adjust portfolio durations to capitalize
- If rates expected to increase → shorten duration
- If rates expected to decrease → lengthen duration
- Futures contracts = quick and inexpensive means to adjust duration (temporary or permanent basis)

**Creating longer duration than available**:
- Some interest-rate environments require very long duration (e.g., duration 15) to accomplish investment objectives
- Bonds with such long duration may not be available
- Buying appropriate number and kind of interest-rate futures contracts can increase portfolio duration to target level

**Example: Duration-matched strategy**:
- Portfolio benchmark: Barclays Capital Intermediate Aggregate Index (duration 3.68)
- Portfolio market value: $48,109,810 (March 31, 2011)
- Portfolio current duration: 2.97 (shown in Exhibit 29.3)
- Portfolio has less interest-rate exposure than benchmark for parallel yield curve shift

**Calculating target dollar duration**:
- Target duration = benchmark duration = 3.68
- Portfolio target dollar duration = 3.68% × $48,109,810 = **$1,770,110**
- Portfolio current dollar duration = 2.97% × $48,109,810 = **$1,428,594**
- Difference = $341,516

**Using futures to increase duration**:
- Need to increase dollar duration by $341,516
- Use 5-year Treasury note futures contract (futures price March 31, 2011: 116.79)
- Dollar duration of 5-year futures for 100-bps change ≈ $5,022
- Dollar duration of futures position = $5,022 × *C* (where *C* = number of contracts)
- Solving: $5,022 × *C* = $341,516 → **C = 68 contracts**
- Buying 68 contracts increases dollar duration by $341,516 for 100-bps change
- Notional amount: $100,000 × 68 = $6,800,000
- Market value of position: (116.79/100) × $100,000 × 68 = **$7,941,720**

**General formula**:
$$\text{approximate number of futures contracts} = \frac{\text{portfolio target dollar duration} - \text{portfolio current dollar duration}}{\text{dollar duration of futures contract}}$$ (Equation 29.7)

- Negative value = contracts to sell; positive value = contracts to buy

**Duration reduction example**:
- If manager wants duration = 90% of benchmark (0.90 × 3.68 = 3.31)
- Portfolio target dollar duration = 3.31% × $48,109,810 = $1,592,435
- Number of contracts = ($1,592,435 − $1,428,594) / $5,022 = **33 contracts**

**Important caveat**:
- Matching duration doesn't mean all interest-rate risk attributes match
- Duration can be matched, but convexity and key rate durations may be mismatched
- Portfolio managers use other hedging instruments to neutralize key rate duration and convexity differences

### Hedging with Futures

**Hedging fundamentals**:
- Special case of interest-rate risk management where **target duration = zero**
- Number of futures to short = current portfolio dollar duration ÷ dollar duration of futures contract
- For individual bond hedging, more detailed analysis needed

**Hedging mechanics**:
- Hedger takes futures position as **temporary substitute** for cash market transactions to be made later
- If cash and futures prices move together, losses in one position offset by profits in the other
- Outcome depends on relationship between cash price and futures price at both placement and lifting of hedge

**Basis and basis risk**:
- **Basis** = difference between cash price and futures price
- **Basis risk** = risk that basis will change unpredictably

**Cross hedging**:
- Bond to be hedged ≠ bond underlying futures contract
- May involve substantial basis risk
- Unhedged position exposed to price risk; hedged position substitutes basis risk for price risk

**Short (sell) hedge**:
- Protects against decline in cash price of bond
- Futures contracts sold
- Hedger fixes future cash price, transfers price risk to futures buyer
- Example: Pension fund manager needs to liquidate bonds in 40 days for $5M payment — sells bonds in futures market to lock in selling price if rates rise

**Long (buy) hedge**:
- Protects against increase in cash price of bond
- Hedger buys futures contract to lock in purchase price
- Used when substantial cash contributions expected and manager concerned rates will fall
- Also used when bonds maturing soon and manager expects rates to fall — locks in reinvestment rate

**Cross hedging complexity**:
- Involves two relationships:
  1. Cheapest-to-deliver security and futures contract
  2. Security to be hedged and cheapest-to-deliver security

### The Hedge Ratio

**Purpose**:
- Minimize risk in cross hedge by choosing right hedge ratio
- Use gains/losses from futures to offset difference between target sale price and actual sale price

**Hedge ratio formula**:
$$\text{hedge ratio} = \frac{\text{volatility of bond to be hedged}}{\text{volatility of hedging instrument}}$$ (Equation 29.8)

- If bond to be hedged is more volatile than hedging instrument, more hedging instrument needed

**Volatility definition for hedging**:
- Concerned with volatility in **absolute dollar terms**
- Must know precise point in time (when hedge will be lifted) and price/yield at which to calculate volatility
- Relevant point = date hedge will be lifted
- Relevant yield = target yield
- "Volatility of bond to be hedged" in equation (29.8) = **price value of basis point for bond on date hedge delivered**

**Example application**:
- December 24, 2007: Investor owned $10M par value Procter & Gamble 5.55% bonds of March 5, 2037
- Sold March 2008 Treasury bond futures for hedge
- Demonstrates volatility weighting leads to correct hedge ratio

<!-- pp. 1021-1040 -->

## Cross Hedging with Treasury Futures

### Detailed Cross Hedge Example: P&G Bond with Treasury Futures

**Cross hedge scenario**: Hedging P&G 5.55% 3/5/2037 bond (nondeliverable) using Treasury bond futures
- P&G bond trading at 5.754% yield, price 97.127
- Treasury 6.25% 8/15/2023 is **cheapest-to-deliver (CTD)** at 4.643% yield, price 117.719, conversion factor 1.0246
- Treasury futures contract at 114.375
- Spread between P&G and CTD: 111.1 basis points (assumed constant)
- Target sale date: March 31, 2008

**Calculating target forward prices**:
- CTD target forward price = conversion factor × futures price = 1.0246 × 114.375 = 117.1886
- CTD target forward yield = 4.670%
- P&G target forward yield = 4.670% + 111.1 bp spread = 5.781%
- P&G target forward price (given 5.55% coupon, 3/5/2037 maturity) = 96.768

**Price value of a basis point (PVBP)**:
- CTD issue: 0.1207
- P&G bond: 0.1363

**Hedge ratio calculation**:
```
hedge ratio = (PVBP of bond to be hedged / PVBP of CTD issue) × conversion factor for CTD issue
hedge ratio = (0.1363 / 0.1207) × 1.0246 = 1.157
```

**Number of contracts to short**:
```
number of contracts = hedge ratio × (par value to be hedged / par value of contract)
= 1.157 × ($10,000,000 / $100,000)
= 1.157 × 100
= 116 contracts (rounded)
```

**Effectiveness**: Exhibit 29.4 shows futures hedge locks in target forward amount of $9,678,000 for $10 million par value of P&G bond

### Adjusting the Hedge Ratio for Yield Spread Changes

**Problem**: Initial calculation assumes **constant yield spread** between CTD and bond to be hedged—this is unrealistic
- Yield spreads vary with maturity, rate levels, and many unpredictable factors
- Hedge ratio must be adjusted to account for changing spreads

**Revised hedge ratio formula**:
```
hedge ratio = (PVBP of bond to be hedged / PVBP of CTD issue)
              × conversion factor for CTD issue × adjustment factor
```

### Two Approaches for Estimating Adjustment Factor

#### 1. Regression Approach

**Regression model**:
```
yield change on bond to be hedged = a + b × yield change on CTD issue + error
```

- Estimate **yield beta** (b) from historical data using regression
- **Yield beta** = expected relative change in yield between the two bonds
- Example: P&G 5.55% 3/5/2037 vs Treasury 6.25% 8/15/2023
- Data: Daily yields from February 28, 2007 to December 21, 2007 (Exhibit 29.5)

**Yield beta results** (three different time periods tested):
- Prior 30 trading days ending December 21, 2007: **0.906**
- Prior 90 trading days ending December 21, 2007: **0.894**
- Prior 218 trading days ending December 21, 2007: **0.906**

**Interpretation**: Yield beta ≈ 0.90 means P&G bond yields move **10% less** than CTD issue yields
- Must account for this in hedge ratio calculation
- Multiply earlier hedge ratio by 0.90
- Instead of shorting 116 contracts, only **105 contracts** should be shorted

**Final formula with yield beta**:
```
hedge ratio = (PVBP of bond to be hedged / PVBP of CTD issue)
              × conversion factor for CTD issue × yield beta
```

#### 2. Pure Volatility Adjustment

**Pure volatility adjustment formula**:
```
pure volatility adjustment = std. dev. of yield change for bond to be hedged / std. dev. of yield change for CTD issue
```

**Results** (three different time periods):
- Prior 30 trading days: **1.011**
- Prior 90 trading days: **1.064**
- Prior 218 trading days: **1.084**

**Key difference from regression approach**: Adjustment differs depending on time period used, and number of contracts to be shorted would be **greater** (adjustment > 1)

### Change in the CTD Issue

**Impact of CTD shifts**: Different yield levels at hedge lift date may result in:
- Different yield spread from original assumption
- Different acceptable CTD issue
- Can construct scenarios (similar to Exhibit 29.4) to assess hedge outcome under various assumptions

### Creating Synthetic Securities for Yield Enhancement

**Synthetic security creation**:
- Combine futures contract position with deliverable instrument to create cash market security synthetically
- **Arbitrage opportunity** if synthetic security yield ≠ cash market security yield

**Example: Creating synthetic 3-month Treasury bill**:
- Own 20-year Treasury bond
- Sell Treasury futures calling for delivery of that bond 3 months from now
- Effectively shortens bond maturity to 3 months
- Long bond + short futures = long 3-month riskless security
- Locks in price to be received 3 months ahead (the futures price)

**Fundamental relationship**:
```
RSP = CBP - FBP
```
where:
- RSP = riskless short-term security position
- CBP = cash bond position
- FBP = futures bond position

**Alternative formulations**:
```
CBP = RSP + FBP  (cash bond = synthetic short-term security + long futures)
FBP = CBP - RSP  (long futures = long cash bond + short riskless security)
```

**Key insight**: Long futures position can be created synthetically by:
- Taking long position in cash market bond
- Shorting short-term riskless security (equivalent to borrowing money)
- This is precisely how theoretical futures price was derived earlier
- If actual futures price > theoretical price, sell futures and create synthetic long futures with borrowed funds

**Market efficiency note**: Yield enhancement opportunities should be temporary in efficient markets, but synthetic securities remain useful for hedging positions lacking liquidity in cash markets

### Allocating Funds between Stocks and Bonds

**Traditional approach problems**:
1. Transaction costs (commissions, bid-ask spreads)
2. Market impact costs
3. Disruption of portfolio managers' activities

**Example**: Pension sponsor wants to shift $1 billion allocation from 50/50 stocks/bonds to 30/70 stocks/bonds
- Traditional: Sell $200 million stocks, buy $200 million bonds

**Futures alternative**: Use interest-rate futures + stock index futures
- Buy appropriate number of interest-rate futures
- Sell appropriate number of stock index futures
- Maintain or slowly liquidate futures positions as cash markets shift

**Advantages of futures approach**:
1. **Lower transaction costs**
2. **Market impact avoided or reduced** (allows more time to execute cash trades)
3. **Portfolio managers not disrupted**

**Formula for interest-rate futures contracts needed**:
```
approximate number of contracts = (dollar duration for target bond allocation - dollar duration for current bond allocation) / dollar duration of futures contract
```

## KEY POINTS

- Futures contract = agreement between buyer/seller and exchange/clearinghouse to take/make delivery at futures price at settlement/delivery date
- **Clearinghouse** guarantees both parties will perform and allows unwinding positions without dealing with original counterparty
- Margin requirements: initial, maintenance, and variation margins
- **Forward contract** differs from futures: nonstandardized terms (individually negotiated), no clearinghouse, often thin/nonexistent secondary markets
- Popular short-term interest-rate futures: Eurodollar futures, SOFR futures, EURIBOR futures (all cash settlement)
- Two U.S. Treasury bond futures contracts:
  1. Treasury bond futures: deliverable bonds must have 15-25 years to maturity
  2. Ultra Treasury bond futures: deliverable bonds must have 25+ years to maturity
- **Theoretical futures price** = cash/spot price + cost of carry
- Cost of carry = financing cost - cash yield on underlying security
- Yield curve shape affects cost of carry
- Actual futures price departs from theoretical price due to delivery options granted to seller (in Treasury futures, these options reduce actual futures price below theoretical)
- **Buying futures adds dollar duration** to portfolio; **selling futures reduces** portfolio dollar duration
- Interest-rate futures contracts used to: control portfolio duration, hedge portfolio/bond positions, enhance returns when mispriced, efficiently allocate funds between stocks/bonds

## QUESTIONS

(27 questions covering futures vs forwards, counterparty risk, cost of carry, LIBOR/SOFR/EURIBOR contracts, margin effects, delivery options, theoretical pricing, conversion factors, hedging mechanics including hedge ratios and yield beta adjustments, duration management, synthetic securities, and asset allocation strategies)

**Notable footnotes**:
- **Mark Paltrowitz** (BlackRock Solutions) provided hypothetical portfolio and analytics for duration/hedging examples
- **Peter Ru** provided Exhibit 29.4 illustration
- References to **Roger Clarke**, **Robert Arnott**, **Frank J. Fabozzi**, and **Mark Zurak/Ravi Dattatreya** on asset allocation using futures

