## Chapter 30: Interest-Rate Options

### Options Defined

- **Option**: contract granting buyer the right (not obligation) to purchase from or sell to writer a designated instrument at a specified price within a specified time period
- **Option price/premium**: sum paid by buyer to seller for this right
- **Strike/exercise price**: price at which instrument may be bought or sold
- **Expiration date**: date after which option is void
- **American option**: exercisable any time up to and including expiration
- **European option**: exercisable only on expiration date
- **Call option**: right to purchase designated instrument from writer
- **Put option**: right to sell designated instrument to writer
- **Long the option**: buyer's position; **short the option**: writer's (seller's) position

### Differences Between Options and Futures

- Option buyer has **right but not obligation** to perform; seller has obligation
- Futures: both parties obligated to perform
- Futures buyer pays nothing upfront; option buyer pays premium
- **Risk/reward asymmetry**:
  - Futures: long position gains/loses dollar-for-dollar with price changes
  - Options: long retains upside potential but limits downside to option price
  - Maximum loss for option buyer: option price paid
  - Maximum profit for option seller: option price received

### Types of Interest-Rate Options

#### Options on Physicals

- **Options on physicals**: underlying instrument is cash debt instrument
- Most liquid exchange-traded option: CME Group's Treasury bond options
- **Over-the-counter (OTC) options** increasingly popular on Treasury and mortgage-backed securities
- OTC options purchased by institutional investors wanting to **hedge specific security risk**
  - Example: thrift hedging specific mortgage pass-through security position
  - Maturity typically matches hedge period, so liquidity less critical
- OTC options available on **yield curve shape** or **yield spreads** (mortgage pass-throughs vs Treasuries, double A corporates vs Treasuries)

#### Exchange-Traded Futures Options

- **Futures option**: gives buyer right to buy/sell designated futures contract at designated price during option life
- **Call futures option**: right to purchase (go long) one designated futures contract at exercise price
  - If exercised, buyer acquires long position, writer acquires short position in futures
- **Put futures option**: right to sell (go short) one designated futures contract at exercise price
  - If exercised, buyer acquires short position, writer acquires long position in futures

##### Exercising a Futures Option

- Upon exercise, futures price set equal to exercise price
- Position immediately **marked to market** at current futures price
- **Economic benefit transferred** at exercise:
  - **Call option**: writer pays buyer difference between current futures price and exercise price
  - **Put option**: writer pays buyer difference between exercise price and current futures price

**Example — Call option exercise:**
- Exercise price: 85; current futures price: 95
- Call buyer assigned long position at 85, call writer assigned short position at 85
- Positions marked to market at 95
- Long gains 10, short loses 10
- Writer pays exchange 10, buyer receives 10
- Buyer can liquidate at 95 or hold long position with realized gain of 10

**Example — Put option exercise:**
- Exercise price: 85; current futures price: 60
- Put buyer assigned short position at 85, put writer assigned long position at 85
- Positions marked to market at 60
- Put buyer gains 25, put writer loses 25

##### Margin Requirements

- **Option buyer**: no margin required after paying premium (maximum loss = premium)
- **Option writer**: must deposit margin for futures position plus variation margin as prices move adversely
- Writer also deposits (with exceptions) the option premium received

##### Reasons for Futures Options Popularity

Three reasons futures options dominate options on physicals:

1. **No accrued interest payments** required on Treasury coupon futures options
   - Simpler settlement at exercise (no compensation for accrued interest)
2. **Cleaner instruments** — reduced likelihood of **delivery squeezes**
   - Deliverable supply of futures contracts adequate
   - Physical delivery concerns: instrument might be in short supply at delivery, driving up acquisition price
3. **Easier pricing** — futures contract prices more readily available than bond market prices

##### Specifications for Actively Traded Futures Options

- Options available on all futures contracts (Chapter 29)
- All futures options: **American type**
- Early exercise: buyer notifies clearing corporation, which randomly selects clearing member/customer
- **Treasury bond futures**: delivery months March, June, September, December
- Some futures options expire in **next three quarterly expiration months**
- Trading stops month prior to underlying futures delivery month
- Stop day: first Friday at least five days before first Treasury bond futures notice day
- **Flexible Treasury futures options**: counterparties can customize strike price, expiration date, exercise type (American/European) within CBOT constraints
  - Expiration cannot exceed longest standard option on CBOT
  - Unlike OTC, flexible Treasury futures option **guaranteed by clearing house**
  - Minimum size: 100 contracts

### Intrinsic Value and Time Value

- **Option cost** = intrinsic value + premium over intrinsic value
- Premium over intrinsic value = **time value**

#### Intrinsic Value of an Option

- **Intrinsic value**: economic value if exercised immediately
- Buyer won't exercise if no economic gain results
- Intrinsic value **cannot be less than zero**

##### Call Options

- **Call intrinsic value** = bond price − strike price
- Example: strike $100, bond $105 → intrinsic value $5
- **In-the-money**: call has intrinsic value (bond price > strike)
- **Out-of-the-money**: strike exceeds bond price (zero intrinsic value)
- **At-the-money**: strike equals bond price (zero intrinsic value)

##### Put Options

- **Put intrinsic value** = strike price − bond price
- Example: strike $100, bond $92 → intrinsic value $8
- **In-the-money put**: bond price < strike
- **Out-of-the-money put**: bond price > strike
- **At-the-money put**: bond price = strike

#### Time Value of an Option

- **Time value** = option price − intrinsic value
- Buyer pays premium hoping market yield changes will increase option value before expiration
- Example: call with strike $100, bond $105, option price $9 → time value $4
- If bond $90 (out-of-the-money), entire $9 is time value

##### Realizing Option Value

Two ways to realize value:

1. **Exercise the option**
   - Futures option: assigned position at exercise price, paid difference between current and strike price
   - Can then sell futures at current price
   - Example: strike $100, option price $9, futures $105 → exercise yields $5, sell for $5 total
   - **Loses time value** (in this case, $4)

2. **Sell the option** — preferable to preserve time value
   - Example: sell option for $9 instead of exercising (preserves $4 time value)

- Whether option exercised early depends on whether **total proceeds at expiration > holding and reinvesting cash proceeds**

### Profit and Loss Profiles for Naked Option Strategies

- **Naked option strategies**: only one option position on a bond, no other positions
- Profiles assume each position **held to expiration** (not exercised earlier)
- No transaction costs assumed
- Four strategies: (1) long call, (2) short call, (3) long put, (4) short put

#### Long Call Strategy (Buying Call Options)

- Straightforward strategy to participate in anticipated interest rate **decrease** (bond price increase)
- Example: 8% coupon bond, par $100, 20 years 1 month to maturity
  - Call expires in 1 month, strike $100, option price $3
  - Currently at-the-money (bond at par, yield 8%)

**Profit/loss depends on bond price at expiration:**

1. **Bond < $100** (yield > 8%): don't exercise, lose entire $3 premium (maximum loss)
2. **Bond = $100** (yield = 8%): no economic value, lose $3
3. **Bond $100-$103** (yield 7.70%-8%): exercise profitable but doesn't cover $3 cost
   - Example: yield 7.8%, bond $102 → gain $2, net loss $1
4. **Bond = $103** (yield ~7.70%): **break-even** (gain $3 offsets $3 cost)
5. **Bond > $103** (yield < 7.70%): realize profit
   - Example: yield 6.8%, bond $113 → profit $13, net $10 after option cost

- **Maximum loss**: $3 (option price)
- **Unlimited upside potential**
- Break-even: $103 (strike + option premium)

**Comparison with Long Bond Strategy:**

- Long bond: gains/loses dollar-for-dollar with bond price
- Long call: **limits downside to $3** but retains upside (reduced by $3)
- If yield unchanged: bond has no gain/loss, call loses $3
- If yield falls significantly: both profit, but call profit $3 less than bond

**Leverage example:**
- $100 invested at option price $3 → can buy 33.33 call options for $100 par bonds
- If yield drops to 6%: bond price $123.11
- Long call profit: $670.26 ($23.11 × 33.33 − $100) = **670% return on $100**
- Long bond profit: $23.11 = **23% return on $100**
- Greater leverage attracts speculators
- Drawback: if yield unchanged, long call loses entire $100; long bond has no loss

#### Short Call Strategy (Selling or Writing Call Options)

- Investor believes interest rates will **rise or change very little**
- Profit/loss profile: **mirror image** of long call
  - Short call profit/loss = negative of long call profit/loss
- **Maximum profit**: option price ($3)
- **Maximum loss**: unlimited (how high bond price can rise)

#### Long Put Strategy (Buying Put Options)

- Strategy to benefit from expected interest rate **increase** (bond price decrease)
- Example: 8% coupon bond, par $100, 20 years 1 month to maturity
  - Put strike $100, option price $2
  - Currently at-the-money (bond $100, yield 8%)

**Profit/loss outcomes:**

1. **Bond > $100** (yield < 8%): don't exercise, lose $2 (maximum loss)
2. **Bond = $100** (yield = 8%): don't exercise, lose $2
3. **Bond $98-$100** (yield ~8.2%): exercise but doesn't cover $2 cost
   - Example: yield 8.6%, bond $99.03 → gain $0.97, net loss $1.03
4. **Bond = $98** (yield ~8.2%): **break-even** (gain $2 offsets $2 cost)
5. **Bond < $98** (yield > 8.2%): realize profit
   - Example: yield 10.6%, bond $78.58 → profit $19.42 ($21.42 gain − $2 cost)

- **Maximum loss**: $2 (option price)
- **Substantial profit potential** (theoretical maximum if bond falls to zero)
- Loss limited to option price; profit potential substantial

**Comparison with Short Bond Strategy:**

Long put vs short bond (both profit if yields rise/price falls):

1. **Bond increases > $100**: put loses $2, short bond can lose much more
   - Example: bond $125.84 (yield 5.8%) → short seller pays $25.84 to cover
2. **Bond = $100**: put loses $2, short bond breaks even
3. **Bond $98-$100** (yield ~8.2%): put loses < $2, short bond has small profit
<!-- pp. 1061-1080 -->

## Chapter 30: Bond Options (continued)

### Short Put Strategy

**Short put strategy** (writing/selling put options) is used when investor expects rates to fall or stay flat (bond prices increase/stable).

- Profit/loss profile is mirror image of long put
- Maximum loss: limited only by how low bond price can fall at expiration minus premium received
- Maximum profit: premium received (capped)
- Use case: expect stable or rising bond prices

Strategy comparison table — at $99.02 price (8.1% yield):
- Long put: loses $1.02
- Short bond: profits $0.98
- At $98 (8.2% yield): long put breaks even, short bond profits $2
- Below $98: both profitable, but long put always $2 less profitable than short bond

### Time Value of Money Considerations

Option buyer must pay premium upfront:
- Either finance the purchase or forgo interest income until expiration
- Option seller can invest the premium received
- Break-even prices differ for buyer vs. seller when time value considered
- **For coupon bonds**: must account for reinvestment income between purchase and expiration
- Financing/opportunity costs affect long/short bond positions
- Text ignores time value for simplicity in remaining examples

### Put-Call Parity Relationship and Equivalent Positions

**Put-call parity**: relationship between call and put prices on same underlying, same strike, same expiration

Example strategy (bond at $100, call at $3, put at $2):
- Buy bond ($100)
- Sell call ($3)
- Buy put ($2)
- **Result**: $1 profit regardless of bond price at expiration

This reveals the arbitrage-free relationship. For **European options** (ignoring time value):

**P_po = P_co + S - P_b** (Equation 30.1)

Where:
- P_po = put option price
- P_co = call option price
- S = strike price
- P_b = current bond price

For **coupon bonds** (with time value):

**P_po = P_co + PV(S) + PV(coupon) - P_b** (Equation 30.3)

Where PV(S) = present value of strike, PV(coupon) = present value of coupon payments

> "Ignoring time value of money and considering European options, the outcome from the following position must be one of no arbitrage profits: long the bond + short call option + long put option = 0" (Equation 30.1)

**Equivalent positions** derived from put-call parity:
- Long bond + short call = short put
- Short bond + short put = short call
- Long bond + long put = long call
- Short bond + long call = long put
- Long call + short put = long bond
- Long put + short call = short bond

Covered call position (long bond + short call) has same profit profile as short put position.

### Option Price Determinants

**Six factors influencing option price:**
1. Current price of underlying instrument
2. Strike price
3. Time to expiration
4. Short-term risk-free interest rate over option life
5. Coupon rate on bond
6. Expected volatility of yields/prices over option life

Impact depends on: (1) call vs. put, (2) American vs. European, (3) bond vs. futures contract

#### Current Price of Underlying Instrument
- **Call**: price increases as underlying price increases
- **Put**: price increases as underlying price decreases

#### Strike Price
- **Call**: higher strike = lower option price
- **Put**: higher strike = higher option price

#### Time to Expiration
- **American options** (calls and puts): longer time = higher price
- **European options**: impact depends on whether put or call (no general rule)

#### Short-Term Risk-Free Interest Rate
- **Call on bond**: increases as rates rise
- **Put on bond**: decreases as rates rise
- **Futures options**: both call and put prices decrease as rates rise

#### Coupon Rate
- **Call options**: coupons reduce price (makes holding bond more attractive than option)
- **Put options**: coupons increase price
- Coupon-bearing bonds: call options priced lower, put options priced higher than non-coupon equivalents

#### Expected Volatility
As expected volatility increases, option price increases. Greater volatility = greater probability of favorable movement for option buyer.

### Models for Pricing Options

**Option pricing models** determine theoretical value of options on bonds and bond futures.

#### Black-Scholes Option Pricing Model

Used for equity options but **limited for bonds**. Formula for European call on non-dividend stock:

**C = SN(d₁) - Xe^(-rt)N(d₂)** (Equation 30.6)

Where:
- d₁ = [ln(S/X) + (r + 0.5s²)t] / (s√t)
- d₂ = d₁ - s√t
- S = current stock price
- X = strike price
- r = short-term risk-free rate
- s = standard deviation of stock return
- t = time to expiration (fraction of year)
- N(·) = cumulative normal distribution

**Three critical limitations for interest-rate options:**

1. **Probability distribution assumption**: allows unlimited upside for bond prices. Reality: bond price capped (zero-coupon bond can't exceed $100; coupon bond capped at coupons + maturity value). Black-Scholes permits negative interest rates, producing nonsensical valuations.

2. **Constant short-term rate assumption**: inappropriate for interest-rate options since the option price changes *as* rates change along the yield curve.

3. **Constant variance assumption**: bond price volatility declines as bond approaches maturity (contradicts model).

Example calculation (3-year zero-coupon bond, strike $88, current price $83.96, 2 years to expiration, 10% volatility, 6% risk-free rate):
- d₁ = 0.5869, d₂ = 0.4455
- Call price = $8.116

But for strike $100.25 (out-of-the-money):
- d₁ = -0.3346, d₂ = -0.4761
- Call price = $2.79

> "Well, consider that this is a call option on a zero-coupon bond that will *never* have a value greater than its maturity value of $100. Consequently, a call option struck at $100.25 must have a value of zero. Yet, the Black-Scholes option pricing model tells us that the value is $2.79!"

The model's flawed assumptions make it unsuitable for pricing interest-rate options.

#### Arbitrage-Free Binomial Model

Proper approach: **arbitrage-free model incorporating the yield curve**. Most popular: **Black-Derman-Toy model**.

Uses binomial interest-rate tree from Chapter 19 to value European options on bonds.

**Example**: 2-year European call on 5.25% 3-year Treasury, strike 99.25
- Uses same interest-rate tree and volatility assumption (10% per year) as Chapter 19
- Exhibit 30.11: Treasury bond values (excluding coupon) at year 2 nodes: 98.5884, 99.7328, 100.6888
- Call value at each node calculated by comparing bond price to strike
- Backward induction using discount rates from binomial tree
- **Call option value = $0.55707**

**Example**: 2-year European put, strike 99.25
- Put values at year 2 nodes shown in Exhibit 30.12
- **Put option value = $0.15224**

**Verification of put-call parity** (Equation 30.3):
- P_b = 102.075 (from Chapter 19)
- PV(S) = 99.25/(1.0401)² = 91.7446
- PV(coupon) = 5.25/1.035 + 5.25/(1.0401)² = 9.9255
- Right side: 0.15224 + 91.7446 + 9.9255 - 102.075 = 0.15217
- Left side (put value): 0.15224
- Discrepancy due to rounding — parity holds

#### Implied Volatility

**Implied volatility**: volatility estimated by assuming option is correctly priced, then solving for volatility using pricing model and observed option price.

Process:
1. Observe market option price
2. Use option pricing model with known factors (price, strike, time, rate, coupon)
3. Solve for volatility that produces observed price

Example: if model produces implied yield volatility of 12%:
- Manager expects higher volatility → option undervalued
- Manager expects lower volatility → option overvalued

> "Trading and investment strategies in this market involve buying and selling volatility."

Can also compute fair value using expected volatility — produces same cheap/expensive conclusions.

### Models for Options on Bond Futures

**Fischer Black model**: most common for futures options, initially for European options on forward contracts.

**C = e^(-rt)[FN(d₁) - XN(d₂)]**
**P = e^(-rt)[XN(-d₂) - FN(-d₁)]**

Where:
- d₁ = [ln(F/X) + 0.5s²t] / (s√t)
- d₂ = d₁ - s√t
- F = futures price
- X = strike price

**Two problems:**
1. Same yield curve issues as Black-Scholes (doesn't recognize yield curve)
2. Developed for European options; Treasury futures options are American

**Barone-Adesi and Whaley extension**: adapted Black model to American options on futures contracts. Used by CBOT for flexible Treasury futures options. Still has first problem (equity-based assumptions).

Despite limitations, Black model is most popular for Treasury futures options.

#### Computing Implied Volatility

Black model widely used to compute **implied volatility from Treasury bond futures options**. Investment houses publish these; available through data vendors.

**Converting price volatility to yield volatility:**
- Implied volatilities from Black model are *price* volatilities of futures contract
- Conversion requires duration of cheapest-to-deliver Treasury bond
- From Chapter 4: approximate percentage price change = duration × change in yield
- Therefore: **yield volatility = price volatility / duration**

#### Selection and Interpretation of Implied Volatility

Implied volatility varies by strike price for same expiration month. Observed pattern since late 1980s:

- **Volatility smile**: in-the-money and out-of-the-money options have higher implied volatility than at-the-money options (U-shaped curve)
- **Volatility skew**: more recently, implied volatility *decreases* with strike price

Standard practice: use implied volatility of at-the-money or nearest-to-the-money option.

**Interpretation caveat**: implied yield volatility of X% assumes:
1. Market prices option correctly
2. Market uses the specific pricing model (e.g., Black model) to price the option

> "Most probably, both assumptions are unrealistic. Given these assumptions, one may interpret that the option market expects a *constant* annualized yield volatility of X% over the life of the option (i.e., to the option's maturity date)."

Neither assumption typically holds — interpret with caution.

### Sensitivity of Option Price to Change in Factors

Portfolio managers need to know sensitivity of option price to changes in:
- Price of underlying bond
- Time to expiration
- Expected volatility

#### Call Option Price and Price of Underlying Bond

Exhibit 30.13 shows theoretical call price vs. underlying bond price:
- Horizontal axis: bond price at any point in time
- Vertical axis: call option price
- Relationship is **convex** curve
- Below strike price X: intrinsic value is zero; 45° line from origin is intrinsic value once bond exceeds strike
- **Intrinsic value (0,X)**: when bond price < strike, intrinsic value = 0
- **Intrinsic value (X,∞)**: slope = 1 (increases dollar-for-dollar with bond price)
- Difference between theoretical price and intrinsic value = **time value of option**

**Exhibit 30.14**: tangent line at price p*
- Tangent approximates new option price for small changes in underlying bond price
- For large changes, tangent provides poor approximation
- Convexity means tangent is good for small moves only


<!-- pp. 1081-1100 -->

## Chapter 30: Interest-Rate Options (continued)

### Option Greeks: Delta

**Delta** = rate of change of option price relative to underlying bond price

- Formula: delta = (change in price of call option) / (change in price of underlying bond)
- Delta of 0.4 means $1 change in bond price → ~$0.40 change in option price
- **Deep out-of-the-money options**: delta ≈ 0 (tangent line nearly flat)
  - Example: Strike $100, bond at $20, two months to expiration — bond price increase from $20 to $21 barely affects option value
- **Deep in-the-money options**: delta ≈ 1 (tangent line approaches intrinsic value line slope)
- **At-the-money options**: delta ≈ 0.5

### Gamma

**Gamma** = rate of change of delta as underlying bond price changes

- Formula: gamma = (change in delta) / (change in price of underlying bond)
- Measures convexity of the option price curve
- Important for understanding how delta itself changes with price movements

### Theta (Time Decay)

**Theta** = change in option price as time to expiration decreases

- Formula: theta = (change in price of option) / (decrease in time to expiration)
- Assuming no change in underlying bond price (intrinsic value constant), theta measures how time value changes
- **Option buyers prefer low theta** — slower price decline as expiration approaches
- **Option writers benefit from high theta** — faster time value decay

### Kappa (Vega)

**Kappa** = dollar price change for 1% change in expected price volatility

- Formula: kappa = (change in option price) / (1% change in expected price volatility)
- Measures sensitivity to volatility changes

### Modified Duration of an Option

**Modified duration for an option** = modified duration of underlying instrument × delta × (price of underlying instrument / price of option)

- Duration depends on three factors:
  1. Modified duration of underlying bond
  2. Delta (price responsiveness)
  3. Leverage ratio (price of underlying / price of option)
- Higher underlying price relative to option price → greater leverage → more interest rate exposure per dollar invested
- **Deep-out-of-the-money vs deep-in-the-money**: Out-of-the-money has higher leverage but lower delta; in-the-money has higher delta but lower leverage

**Interest-rate call options**: positive delta → positive modified duration (when rates decline, call option value rises)

**Interest-rate put options**: negative delta → negative modified duration (when rates rise, put option value rises)

## Hedge Strategies with Options

Two popular hedge strategies:
1. **Protective put buying** — hedge against rising rates
2. **Covered call writing** — generate income, partial downside protection

### Hedging Long-Term Bonds with Puts on Futures

**Case study**: Hedge P&G 5.55% 3/5/2037 bond ($10 million par value)
- Bond selling at yield 5.74%
- Use Treasury bond futures with March 2008 settlement
- Put options expire February 22, 2008
- CTD issue: Treasury 6.25% 8/15/2023 trading at 4.643% yield
- Spread assumption: constant 111.1 basis points

**Steps to determine strike price**:
1. Target minimum price for P&G bond: 96.219 (= $9,621,900 for $10M par)
2. Convert to equivalent maximum yield: 5.821%
3. CTD maximum yield (maintaining spread): 4.710% (= 5.821% - 111.1 bp)
4. CTD target forward price: 116.8044
5. Convert to futures price using conversion factor (1.0246): 114.373
6. **Strike price selected: 114.000** (based on available strikes)

**Hedge ratio**: 1.15 (rounded from 1.148)
- Calculated using equation 29.10 from chapter 29
- Price value of basis point: P&G bond 0.1353, CTD issue 0.1208

**Number of put contracts**: 115
- Put option price per contract: $192 (quote: 1.972)
- Total cost: $22,678

**Results** (Exhibit 30.16):
- Effective sale price never less than $9,601,824 (minimum target: $9,621,900)
- As bond prices decline → put options gain value → offset losses
- As bond prices rise → effective sale price increases (unlike futures hedge)
- **Key advantage**: Protects downside but allows upside profit if rates fall

### Covered Call Writing with Futures Options

**Purpose**: Generate premium income, not pure protection against rising rates
- Writer believes market won't move much higher or lower
- Sells out-of-the-money calls against existing bond portfolio
- Premium provides partial protection if rates increase
- **Limited upside**: Liability from short call position increases as rates fall

**Example setup**:
- Same P&G bond, futures at 114.375
- Sell 120 call option on March futures expiring 2/22/2008
- Call option price: 0.512 or $51.20
- Hedge ratio: 1.15, so sell 115 contracts
- Expected maximum price: 103.785

**Mechanics**:
- Effective sale price = actual bond price + premium received - liability from call options
- Liability per call = Max[(futures price - 120), 0] × $1,000 × 115
- Premium collected: 115 × 5,888 = $677,120 total premium income

**Results** (Exhibit 30.18):
- Maximum effective sale price ≈ 103.785 (strike 120 futures = 122.9520 cash, equivalent P&G yield 5.3271%, price 103.273)
- Provides income if market stable
- Limited upside potential — liability increases as prices rise
- **Key difference from protective puts**: Income generation vs. pure protection

### Comparing Alternative Strategies

**Exhibit 30.19** compares three approaches at various bond prices:
1. Futures hedge
2. Protective puts
3. Covered calls

**Key insight**: No "best" strategy — each has trade-offs
- Manager chooses among **probability distributions**, not specific outcomes
- Perfect hedge has no range of outcomes
- Each strategy has advantages/disadvantages — "never get something for nothing"
- Strategy superior at one rate level will be inferior at others

## Chapter 31: Interest-Rate Swaps, Forward-Rate Agreements, Caps, and Floors

### Interest-Rate Swaps

**Interest-rate swap** = agreement between two **counterparties** to exchange periodic interest payments

- Based on **notional principal amount** (predetermined dollar amount)
- Only interest payments exchanged, not principal
- Most common type:
  - **Fixed-rate payer** (floating-rate receiver): pays fixed interest at designated dates
  - **Floating-rate payer** (fixed-rate receiver): pays floating interest based on reference rate
- **Reset frequency** = how often floating-rate payer must pay

**Reference rates**: LIBOR most common
- **LIBOR** (London Interbank Offered Rate) = rate prime banks offer on Eurodollar deposits to other prime banks
- Global cost of bank borrowing
- Multiple maturities: 1-month, 3-month, 6-month LIBOR
- Other reference rates: Treasury bill, commercial paper, banker's acceptances, CDs, federal funds rate, prime rate

**Example swap**: Party X and Party Y, five years, $50 million notional
- X pays Y 10% per year
- Y pays X 6-month LIBOR
- Payments exchanged every six months
- X = fixed-rate payer, Y = fixed-rate receiver
- X pays $2.5 million (10% × $50M / 2) every six months
- Y pays 6-month LIBOR × $50M / 2 (if LIBOR = 7%, Y pays $1.75M)

### Entering into a Swap and Counterparty Risk

**Entering a swap**:
- Over-the-counter instruments (not exchange-traded)
- Through securities firm or commercial bank that transacts swaps
- Two methods:
  1. **Broker**: arrange/broker swap between two parties
  2. **Dealer** (**swap dealer**): take the other side, hedge position in other securities

**Swap dealers**: Goldman Sachs, etc.
- Institutional investor looks to dealer to satisfy obligations
- Dealer looks to institutional investor to fulfill obligations
- **Counterparty risk** = default risk — risk that other party fails to fulfill obligations
- More significant in swaps than futures/exchange-traded options (clearinghouse guarantees performance)
- Not all banks can be swap dealers — high credit rating required
- Some securities firms created separately capitalized subsidiaries with high credit ratings to act as dealers

### Interpreting a Swap Position

Two interpretations:
1. **Package of forward/futures contracts**
2. **Package of cash flows from buying/selling cash market instruments**

**Package of Forward Contracts**:
- Consider party X (pays 10%, receives 6-month LIBOR, $50M notional)
- X agrees to buy 6-month LIBOR for $2.5 million each period
- This is a 6-month forward contract on 6-month LIBOR
- If rates rise to 11%, 6-month LIBOR price is higher → gain for fixed-rate payer (long forward)
- Fixed-rate receiver = short 6-month forward contract on 6-month LIBOR
- **Implicit forward contract** exists for each exchange date
- Swap pricing depends on package of forward contracts with same settlement dates and underlying index

**Not redundant despite being package of forwards** — swaps are distinct financial instruments for several reasons (though text notes they serve similar economic functions)


<!-- pp. 1101-1120 -->

## Interest-Rate Swaps (continued)

### Why Swaps Over Forward Contracts

Three reasons swaps dominate forwards for interest-rate management:

- **Maturity advantage**: Swaps can extend 15+ years; forward/futures contracts have shorter maturities
- **Transaction efficiency**: Single swap achieves what requires multiple separately-negotiated forward contracts
- **Liquidity**: Since 1981 establishment, swap market provides superior liquidity especially for long-dated instruments

### Swap as Package of Cash Market Instruments

Example transaction decomposes swap into bond + loan:

- Buy $50M 5-year floating-rate bond (pays 6-month LIBOR semiannually)
- Finance via $50M 5-year borrowing at 10% fixed rate (paid semiannually)

**Result**: Net position = receive LIBOR, pay $2.5M semiannually — identical to fixed-rate payer position

**Key insight**: Fixed-rate payer = long floating-rate bond + short fixed-rate bond (borrowing)

**Fixed-rate receiver position**: Long fixed-rate bond + short floating-rate bond (floating-rate liability)

### Swap Terminology and Conventions

**Trade dates**:
- **Trade date**: Commitment date when counterparties agree to swap
- **Effective date**: When swap begins accruing interest
- **Maturity date**: When swap stops accruing interest

**Position descriptions** (combining cash market and futures jargon):

| Fixed-Rate Payer | Fixed-Rate Receiver |
|------------------|---------------------|
| Pays fixed rate | Pays floating rate |
| Receives floating rate | Receives fixed rate |
| Has bought a swap | Has sold a swap |
| Is long a swap | Is short a swap |
| Is short the bond market | Is long the bond market |

**Market mechanics**:
- Fixed-rate payer = short bond market (benefits from rate increases)
- Fixed-rate receiver = long bond market (benefits from rate declines)
- Can also view as: Fixed-rate payer = exposed to price sensitivities of longer-term liability + floating-rate bond
- Fixed-rate receiver = exposed to price sensitivities of fixed-rate bond + floating-rate liability

### Quoting Convention

Dealer sets floating rate = index (e.g., LIBOR), then quotes the fixed rate spread to Treasury

**Example**: 10-year swap quote "40-50" when Treasury yields 8.35% (10 basis point bid-offer spread):

- **Fixed-rate receiver bid**: Pay LIBOR flat, receive 8.75% (Treasury + 40bp)
- **Fixed-rate payer offer**: Pay 8.85% (Treasury + 50bp), receive LIBOR flat

Fixed rate = Treasury yield with same maturity + spread over Treasury

**Dealer quote "40-50" means**:
- Dealer receives LIBOR / pays fixed at Treasury + 40bp (willing to be fixed-rate receiver)
- Dealer pays LIBOR / receives fixed at Treasury + 50bp (willing to be fixed-rate payer)
- Spread difference = bid-offer spread

### Calculating the Swap Rate

**Core principle**: At initiation, no upfront payments — present value of fixed-rate payments = present value of floating-rate payments

**Example setup** (3-year swap, $100M notional):
- Settlement: January 1, year 1
- Floating payments: Quarterly, actual/360 day count
- Reference rate: 3-month LIBOR
- Term: 3 years

**Floating-rate payment calculation**:

Formula: notional amount × (3-month LIBOR) × (days in period / 360)

First payment (Jan 1 to Mar 31, 90 days, 3-month LIBOR = 4.05%):
$100,000,000 × 0.0405 × (90/360) = $1,012,500

**Future payments hedging**: Use **Eurodollar futures contract** to lock in future 3-month LIBOR rates

Example for Q2 (Apr 1 to Jun 30, 91 days):
- Eurodollar futures settling Jun 30 prices at 95.85
- Implied 3-month LIBOR forward rate = 4.15%
- Payment = $100,000,000 × 0.0415 × (91/360) = $1,049,028

**Critical timing note**: Reference rate at beginning of period *t* determines floating rate paid at end of period *t*

### Forward Discount Factor

**Discounting requirement**: Each cash flow discounted at unique theoretical spot rate

**Spot rates source**: Derived from 3-month LIBOR forward rates (from Eurodollar futures)

**Period forward rate formula**:

period forward rate = annual forward rate × (days in period / 360)

**Forward discount factor** for period *t*:

Forward discount factor = $1 / [(1 + forward rate for period 1)(1 + forward rate for period 2)...(1 + forward rate for period *t*)]

Example calculation (period 4, annual forward rate 4.72%):
- Period forward rate = 4.72% × (92/360) = 1.2062%
- Forward discount factor = $1 / (1.010125 × 1.010490 × 1.011628 × 1.012062) = 0.9568960

### Fixed-Rate Payment Calculation

Formula: notional amount × swap rate × (days in period / 360)

Example (swap rate 4.98%, 90-day quarter):
$100,000,000 × 0.0498 × (90/360) = $1,245,000

**Note**: Same formula as floating payments, but uses swap rate instead of reference rate

### Deriving the Swap Rate

**No-arbitrage condition**: PV of fixed-rate payments = PV of floating-rate payments

**Swap rate formula**:

swap rate = (present value of floating-rate payments) / [Σ notional amount × (days in period *t* / 360) × forward discount factor for period *t*]

**Example calculation** (3-year swap):
- PV of floating payments = $14,052,917
- Denominator sum = $281,764,281
- Swap rate = $14,052,917 / $281,764,281 = 0.049875 = **4.9875%**

**Swap spread determination**: For 3-year swap, use 3-year on-the-run Treasury as benchmark

If 3-year Treasury yields 4.5875%, swap spread = 4.9875% − 4.5875% = **40 basis points**

### Valuing a Swap After Initiation

**Value changes**: Market interest rate movements change floating-rate payments, altering swap value

**Valuation method**:
1. Calculate floating-rate payments using current Eurodollar futures (forward rates)
2. Calculate discount factors from forward rates
3. Calculate present values of both payment streams
4. Swap value = PV of payments received − PV of payments made

**Example** (same 3-year swap, one year later, rates increase):

New floating-rate payments (higher LIBOR):
- Q1 (year 2): $1,312,500 (LIBOR 5.25%)
- Q2 (year 2): $1,448,417 (forward rate 5.73%)
- Subsequent quarters: 5.78% to 6.75%

**Results after rate increase**:
- PV of floating payments = $11,459,496
- PV of fixed payments = $9,473,392
- **Fixed-rate payer value** = $11,459,496 − $9,473,392 = **+$1,986,104**
- **Fixed-rate receiver value** = −$1,986,104

**Key takeaway**: Fixed-rate payer benefits from rate increases (swap value rises); fixed-rate receiver adversely affected (swap value declines)

### Duration of a Swap

**Dollar duration**: Measures interest-rate sensitivity of swap value

Just as with fixed-income contracts, swap value changes as interest rates change — duration quantifies this sensitivity from the perspective of each party


<!-- pp. 1121-1140 -->

### Interest-Rate Swap Dollar Duration

- **Dollar duration of swap** = dollar duration of fixed-rate bond − dollar duration of floating-rate bond
- Fixed-rate receiver position viewed as: long fixed-rate bond + short floating-rate bond
- Floating-rate bond has small dollar duration (closer to reset date = smaller duration)
- **To increase portfolio duration**: enter swap as fixed-rate receiver (leverage interest-rate risk)
- **To decrease portfolio duration**: enter swap as fixed-rate payer

### Application to Portfolio Risk Control

- Interest-rate swaps equivalent to portfolio of forward/futures contracts
- Same duration-adjustment mechanism as futures (chapter 29 reference)
- **Example**: Portfolio value $48,109,810, benchmark is Barclays Capital Intermediate Aggregate Index
  - Index duration: 3.68
  - Portfolio duration: 2.97
  - Target dollar duration: 3.68% × $48,109,810 = $1,770,441
  - Current dollar duration: 2.97% × $48,109,810 = $1,428,861
  - Need to increase by $341,580 for 100-basis-point change
- **5-year at-the-money swap** at 2.42% rate
  - Enter as fixed-rate receiver
  - Notional amount: $7,699,779
  - Dollar duration: $340,881
  - New portfolio dollar duration: $1,769,475 (close to target 3.68)

### Application to Asset/Liability Management

#### Bank Example
- **Assets**: $50 million 5-year commercial loans at 7% fixed rate, interest-only, semiannual payments, principal at maturity
- **Funding**: 6-month CDs at 6-month LIBOR + 40 basis points
- **Risk**: If 6-month LIBOR ≥ 6.6%, no spread income (or loss if higher)
- **Problem**: Lent long-term fixed, borrowed short-term floating

#### Life Insurance Company Example
- **Liabilities**: GIC paying 6% for 5 years on $50 million guaranteed investment contract
- **Assets**: Can invest $50 million in 5-year floating-rate instrument at 6-month LIBOR + 160 basis points
- **Risk**: If 6-month LIBOR falls to 4.4% or less, no spread income
- **Problem**: Lent short-term floating, borrowed long-term fixed

#### Swap Solution
- **5-year interest-rate swap**, $50 million notional
- **Bank terms**: Pay 5.45% fixed semiannually, receive LIBOR
- **Insurance company terms**: Pay LIBOR, receive 5.40% fixed

**Bank outcome**:
- Receives: 7.00% (loans) + 6-month LIBOR (swap)
- Pays: 6-month LIBOR + 0.4% (CDs) + 5.45% (swap) = 5.85% + 6-month LIBOR
- **Locked-in spread**: 115 basis points regardless of LIBOR

**Insurance company outcome**:
- Receives: 1.6% + 6-month LIBOR (floating instrument) + 5.40% (swap) = 7.00% + 6-month LIBOR
- Pays: 6.00% (GIC) + 6-month LIBOR (swap)
- **Locked-in spread**: 100 basis points regardless of LIBOR

- Transaction converts cash flows: bank from fixed to floating, insurance company from floating to fixed
- Called **asset swap** (alters asset cash flows) or **liability swap** (alters liability cash flows)
- Swaps can enhance returns under market imperfections (e.g., insurance company earning 80 bp more with floating + swap vs. direct 5-year fixed-rate bond at 6.8%)

### Creation of Structured Notes Using Swaps

- **Structured MTNs**: Corporations customize medium-term notes for investors wanting to bet on interest rate/currency/stock movements
- Corporation can synthetically fix coupon rate by issuing MTN + entering swap simultaneously
- **Example**: **Arbour Corporation** wants $100 million 5-year fixed-rate MTN at 6.10%
  - Banker recommends inverse-floating-rate MTN instead
  - **Transaction 1**: Issue $100 million 5-year inverse floater with coupon = 13% − LIBOR
  - **Transaction 2**: 5-year swap where Arbour pays LIBOR, receives 7%
  - **Net payment**: (13% − LIBOR) + LIBOR − 7% = 6% (better than 6.10% fixed-rate)
- Using equity and currency swaps, any coupon type can be created

### Variants of the Generic Interest-Rate Swap

- **Plain vanilla/generic swap**: Fixed notional principal, fixed vs. floating payments
- Nongeneric/individualized swaps evolved for asset/liability needs
- Include: varying notional principal, both floating rates, **swaptions**, **forward start swaps**
- Not "bells and whistles" but features managers need to control interest-rate risk

#### Varying Notional Principal Amount Swaps

- **Bullet swap**: Notional principal constant over swap life
- **Amortizing swap**: Notional principal decreases in predetermined way
  - Used when hedged asset amortizes (e.g., typical mortgage loan)
- **Accreting swap**: Notional principal increases over time
- **Roller coaster swap**: Notional principal can rise or fall period to period

#### Basis Swaps and Constant Maturity Swaps

- **Basis swap**: Both parties exchange floating-rate payments based on different reference rates
  - Example: Bank with prime-rate loans but LIBOR-based funding faces **basis risk** (spread between prime and LIBOR changes)
  - Bank pays prime-based floating, receives LIBOR-based floating
- **Constant maturity swap**: Floating leg tied to longer-term rate (e.g., 2-year Treasury) rather than money market rate
  - Reference rate for yield on constant maturity Treasury typically from **Federal Reserve CMT rate**
  - Called **Constant Maturity Treasury swap** if tied to CMT

#### Forward Start Swap

- **Forward start swap**: Swap doesn't begin until future specified date
- Has both beginning date (future) and maturity date
- Swap rate specified at agreement for payments commencing at start date

#### Swaptions

- Options on interest-rate swaps
- Buyer pays fee (**swaption price/premium**) for right to enter swap at future date
- Terms: time to expiration, term of swap, swap rate (**strike rate**)
- American- or European-style exercise
- **Payer swaption**: Right to enter swap paying fixed rate, receiving floating rate
- **Receiver swaption**: Right to enter swap paying floating rate, receiving fixed rate
- **Notation**: "A×B" where A = years to expiration, B = term of swap
  - Example: "3 into 10" = right to enter 10-year swap in 3 years
- Dealers quote ATM swaptions based on assumed volatility; ITM/OTM quotes based on higher volatilities than ATM

**Controlling interest-rate risk** (application from chapter 30):
- Manager wants to increase duration, add interest-rate risk exposure
- With futures: buy Treasury futures
- With swaps: become fixed-rate receiver
- With swaption: buy receiver swaption for nonlinear payoff (upside potential, limited downside)
- **Example**: 1 × 5 ATM receiver European swaption, strike rate 3.26%, 115 bp volatility
  - Cost: $307,705 (notional $14,487,071)
  - Dollar duration added: $340,881 (same as fixed-rate swap)

**Asset-liability management** (application):
- Bank makes 10% fixed-rate payments in swap using commercial loan interest (10%)
- **Risk**: Borrower default means bank can't make swap payments
- **Solution**: Enter receiver swaption to terminate/cancel swap (receive 10% fixed to offset obligation)
- Also protects against prepayment risk (e.g., rates drop to 7%, borrowers prepay, bank obligated to pay 10% but can only reinvest at 7%)

### Forward Rate Agreements

- **FRA**: OTC equivalent of exchange-traded futures on short-term rates (typically LIBOR)
- Elements: contract rate, reference rate, settlement rate, notional amount, settlement date
- Parties agree to buy/sell funds on settlement date
- **Contract rate**: Rate buyer agrees to pay, seller agrees to receive
- **Settlement rate**: Value of reference rate at FRA's settlement date
- **FRA buyer benefits if settlement rate > contract rate** (borrow below market)
- **FRA seller benefits if contract rate > settlement rate** (lend above market)
- Neither benefits if settlement rate = contract rate

**Cash settlement**:
- Party benefiting receives compensation from the other
- If settlement rate ≠ contract rate:
  - Buyer compensated if settlement rate > contract rate
  - Seller compensated if contract rate > settlement rate

**Compensation calculation** (360-day convention):
- Interest differential = (Settlement rate − Contract rate) × (Days in contract / 360) × Notional amount
- If contract rate > settlement rate: Interest differential = (Contract rate − Settlement rate) × (Days in contract / 360) × Notional amount
- Present value of interest differential discounted at settlement rate
- Compensation = Interest differential / [1 + Settlement rate × (Days in contract / 360)]

**Example**: 3-month LIBOR FRA, contract rate 5%, notional $10 million, 91 days to settlement
- Settlement rate 5.5%
- Interest differential = (0.055 − 0.05) × (91/360) × $10,000,000 = $12,638.89
- Compensation = $12,638.89 / [1 + 0.055 × (91/360)] = $12,465.58

**Comparison with futures**:
- **FRA buyer benefits from rate increase** (like being long FRA)
- **Futures buyer benefits from rate decrease** (long fixed-income instrument)
- Underlying differs: FRA = rate, futures = fixed-income instrument
- FRA buyer gains when rates rise and loses when rates fall; opposite for futures

### Interest-Rate Caps and Floors

- **Interest-rate agreement**: One party compensates other at specific periods if designated interest rate (reference rate) differs from predetermined level
- **Interest-rate cap/ceiling**: Agreement where one party pays when reference rate exceeds strike rate
- **Interest-rate floor**: Agreement where one party pays when reference rate falls below strike rate
- **Strike rate**: Predetermined interest-rate level

**Terms include**:
1. Reference rate
2. Strike rate (ceiling or floor)
3. Length of agreement
4. Frequency of settlement
5. Notional principal amount

**Example - Interest-rate cap**:
- C buys cap from D
- Reference rate: 6-month LIBOR
- Strike rate: 8%
- Agreement: 7 years
- Settlement: every 6 months
- Notional principal: $20 million
- D pays C whenever 6-month LIBOR > 8%
- Payment = dollar value of difference × notional principal / 2
- Example: If LIBOR = 11%, D pays C 3% (11% − 8%) × $20 million / 2 = $300,000

**Example - Interest-rate floor**:
- Same terms but floor instead of cap
- If LIBOR = 11%, C receives nothing
- If LIBOR = 7%, D pays C $100,000 (8% − 7% × $20 million / 2)

**Interest-rate collar**: Buying cap + selling floor (or vice versa)
- Commercial banks and investment banking firms write options on caps (**captions**) and floors (**flotions**)

#### Risk/Return Characteristics

- Buyer pays upfront fee (maximum loss and writer's maximum gain)
- Only writer required to perform
- **Cap buyer benefits** if interest rate rises above strike rate (writer compensates)
- **Floor buyer benefits** if interest rate falls below strike rate (writer compensates)

**Conceptual equivalence**:
- Cap/floor equivalent to package of interest-rate options
- **Interest-rate cap** = package of call options on interest rate OR put options on bond
- Cap seller sold package of calls on interest rate OR puts on bond
- **Interest-rate floor** = package of put options on interest rate OR call options on bond
- Floor buyer bought put options on interest rate OR call options on bond
- **Captions and flotions** = options on package of options

#### Valuing Caps and Floors

- Arbitrage-free binomial model (chapter 19) can value caps and floors
- Cap/floor = strip of European options on interest rates
- Each period's cap = **caplet**; sum all caplets = **caplet method** for valuing cap
- Binomial interest-rate tree requires modification for **payment in arrears** (interest rate determined at period start but paid at period end)
- Use Arabic numbers for dates (Date 0, 1, 2, 3) and words for years (Year One, Two, Three)

**Example**: 5.2% 3-year cap, $10 million notional, 1-year reference rates, annual payoff
- Date 0: 1-year rate 3.5%, doesn't exceed 5.2% cap → payoff = $0
- **Year Two caplet** (Date 1 rates: 4.4448% and 5.4289%):
  - If 5.4289%: payoff = (5.4289% − 5.2%) × $10,000,000 = $22,890 at Date 2
  - Present value at Date 1: $22,890/1.054289 = $21,711
  - If 4.4448%: payoff = $0
  - Average at Date 1: $10,855.5
  - Discount to Date 0 at 3.5%: $10,488.41 = $10,488
- **Year Three caplet** (Date 2 rates: 4.6958%, 5.7354%, 7.0053%):
  - Payoffs at Date 3: $0, $53,540, $180,530 (in arrears)
  - Present values at Date 2: $50,636, $168,711
  - Average at Date 1 for each branch, discount back
  - Lower rate (4.4448%): PV = $24,240.56 = $24,241
  - Higher rate (5.4289%): PV = $104,026
  - Discount to Date 0 at 3.5%: $61,964.73 = $61,965

**3-year cap value** = Year One caplet ($0) + Year Two caplet ($10,488) + Year Three caplet ($61,965) = **$72,453**

**Alternative method**: Single binomial tree (exhibit 31.14) — easier, reduces discounting steps

<!-- pp. 1141-1160 -->

## Chapter 31: Interest-Rate Options and Swaps (continued)

### Valuing a Floor

- **Floor valuation** mirrors cap valuation except payoffs occur when interest rate < strike rate
- A **floorlet** is the value of the floor for any single year; sum of floorlets = total floor value
- Can value floors using single binomial tree or caplet approach
- Floor structure: protection buyer receives payment when reference rate falls below strike rate

### Applications: Asset/Liability Management

**Commercial Bank Example: Creating a Collar**
- Bank's problem: borrows short-term (uncertain funding costs) but earns fixed rate on commercial loans
- Solution: Buy a cap to ceiling funding costs, sell a floor to reduce cap purchase cost
- **Collar** = long cap + short floor, creates predetermined range for funding costs
- Trade-off: Bank gives up opportunity to benefit from rate declines below strike rate
- If rates decline, bank doesn't benefit from cap but funding costs fall; if rates decline below floor strike, bank pays floor buyer

**Life Insurance Company Example: GIC with Floating-Rate Investment**
- Company guarantees 9% on 5-year GIC but wants to buy attractive floating-rate instrument
- Risk: rates fall, company can't earn enough to cover 9% guarantee plus spread
- Solution: Buy a floor to set lower bound on investment return while retaining upside from rate increases
- Can sell an interest-rate cap to reduce floor cost, but gives up opportunity to benefit from rate increases above cap strike rate

### Key Points Summary

**Interest-Rate Swap Fundamentals**
- **Interest-rate swap**: agreement to exchange interest payments at designated times
- Generic structure: one party pays **fixed-rate** (fixed-rate payer), other pays **floating-rate** (fixed-rate receiver), based on notional principal
- Swaps alter portfolio duration, cash flow characteristics, or capitalize on perceived market inefficiencies
- Swap position interpretable as package of forward/futures contracts OR package of cash flows from buying/selling cash market instruments

**Swap Valuation and Duration**
- **Swap rate** calculated by finding rate that makes PV of both sides equal
- Value of existing swap = difference in PV of two payment streams
- **Interest-rate sensitivity (duration) from floating-rate payer perspective** = duration of fixed-rate bond minus duration of floating-rate bond
- Most swap interest-rate sensitivity comes from fixed-rate bond (floating-rate bond has small duration)

**Nongeneric Swap Structures**
- **Amortizing, accreting, and roller coaster swaps**: notional amount changes in predetermined way over swap life
- **Basis swaps**: both counterparties pay floating rates
- **Constant Maturity Treasury (CMT) swaps**: both parties pay floating rates
- **Forward start swaps**: swap begins at future date
- **Swaptions** (options on swaps): create portfolio with option-type payoffs—desired duration if rates move favorably, limited adverse movements if rates move opposite direction
- Cost of favorable risk-return relationship = cost of swaptions

**Forward Rate Agreements (FRAs)**
- **FRA** = OTC equivalent of exchange-traded futures contracts on short-term rates, typically LIBOR
- Cash settlement contract
- FRA elements: **contract rate**, **reference rate**, **settlement rate**, **notional amount**, **settlement date**
- Buyer pays contract rate, seller receives contract rate
- Amount exchanged at settlement date = PV of interest differential

**Interest-Rate Agreements**
- **Interest-rate agreement**: one party receives compensation from writer if designated interest rate differs from predetermined level (for upfront premium)
- **Interest-rate cap**: payment if designated rate > strike rate
- **Interest-rate floor**: payment if designated rate < strike rate
- Cap establishes ceiling on funding cost; floor establishes floor return
- **Collar** = buying cap + selling floor

**Cap and Floor Valuation**
- Caps and floors valued using binomial model

## Chapter 32: Credit Default Swaps

### Learning Objectives Overview

- Credit derivatives differ from interest-rate derivatives in addressing **credit risk** rather than interest-rate risk
- Credit risk encompasses: **default risk**, **credit spread risk**, **downgrade risk**
- **Credit default swap (CDS)** is most commonly used credit derivative—simplest form of credit risk transference

### CDS Structure and Parties

**Basic Mechanics**
- Two parties: **credit protection buyer** and **credit protection seller**
- Protection seller provides buyer protection against "credit event" on "something" (for a fee)
- **Reference entity**: issuer of debt instrument for which credit protection is sought
- **Reference obligation**: particular class of debt issue for which credit protection sought
- Example: reference entity = Ford Motor Credit Company; reference obligation = specific Ford Motor Credit Company bond issue

**Types of CDS**
- **Single-name CDS**: only one reference entity or one reference obligation
- **Index CDS**: standardized basket of reference entities
- Each reference entity identified by **RED code** (Reference Entity Data) to ensure buyer and seller agree on specific reference entity
- Payment from protection buyer to seller = **CDS spread** or **swap payment**

### Credit Events

**ISDA Standardization Evolution**
- Pre-1998: lack of standardization hindered credit derivatives development—every trade customized
- 1998: **ISDA** (International Swaps and Derivatives Association) developed standard contract for trading credit derivatives
- **1999 ISDA Credit Derivatives Definitions**: eight credit events for corporate/sovereign debt
- 2001: **Restructuring Supplement** modified restructuring definition
- 2003: **2003 ISDA Credit Derivative Definitions** revised based on high-yield corporate defaults and 2001–2002 Argentina debt crisis
- 2009: "**Big Bang**" update in response to 2008–2009 global financial crisis

**Eight Credit Events (1999 Definitions)**
1. **Bankruptcy**: acts associated with bankruptcy/insolvency laws
2. **Credit event upon merger**
3. **Acceleration**: obligation becomes due/payable before scheduled date due to default
4. **Cross default**
5. **Downgrade**
6. **Failure to pay**: reference entity fails to make contractual payments when due
7. **Repudiation/moratorium**: reference entity disaffirms/challenges validity of obligation
8. **Restructuring**: terms altered to make new terms less attractive to debt holder than original

**Restructuring Controversy**
- **Protection buyer perspective**: wants restructuring included as credit event to maximize protection
- **Protection seller perspective**: prefers not to include—routine loan modifications would trigger payouts
- Dual benefit if reference obligation is loan and protection buyer is lender: (1) payment from seller, (2) accommodating restructuring fosters lender-customer relationship
- **Restructuring Supplement (April 2001)** provided modified definition with limitations:
  - Four or more holders of reference obligation required
  - Supermajority consent (66⅔%) to restructuring required
  - Limits on maturity of physically deliverable reference obligations

**2003 Definitions Update**
- Parties select from four restructuring definitions: (1) no restructuring, (2) "full" or "old" restructuring (1999), (3) "modified restructuring" (Supplement), (4) "modified-modified restructuring" (new for European market)

**"Narrowly Tailored Credit Event" (2019)**
- Response to orchestrated CDS payouts where corporate default did not occur
- Famous example: **Hovnanian** (U.S. homebuilder) and **Blackstone Group**—Blackstone attempted to "manufacture" technical default event to trigger CDS protection it had purchased

### Credit Events for Asset-Backed Securities

**ABS CDS Differences**
- ABSs written on asset-backed securities with unique characteristics
- ISDA **pay-as-you-go (PAUG)** template (June 2005) for ABS
- Focus on **cash flow adequacy** rather than bankruptcy potential (ABS issuer is bankruptcy-remote trust)

**Three ABS Credit Events (PAUG Template)**
1. **Failure to pay**: underlying reference obligation fails to make scheduled interest/principal payment
2. **Writedown**: principal component of underlying reference obligation written down and deemed irrecoverable
3. **Distressed ratings downgrade**: underlying reference obligation downgraded to Caa2/CCC or lower

- PAUG template captures non-default events impacting cash flow of specific reference ABS tranche

### Single-Name CDS Mechanics

**Reference Entities**
- Corporate debt issuer (bonds or leverage loans)
- Sovereign issuer
- Municipal bond issuer
- Tranche of asset-backed security

**Example Structure**
- Reference entity: **XYZ Corporation** (only one bond issue outstanding)
- Underlying: $10 million par value of XYZ bond issue
- Notional amount: $10 million (like interest-rate derivatives)
- **Swap premium (CDS spread)**: 200 basis points (market's perception of credit's default probability)
- CDS spread near zero = very low default probability; very high spread = near bankruptcy

**Payment Mechanics (Quarterly)**
- Standardized payment dates: March 20, June 20, September 20, December 20
- Day count convention: **actual/360** (actual days in quarter / 360 days per year)
- Quarterly payment determined using bond market day count conventions

**Pre-2009 CDS Spread Calculation**
```
Quarterly swap premium payment =
  notional amount × agreed-upon CDS spread × (actual no. of days in quarter / 360)
```
- No upfront payment between parties
- Example: $10M notional, 200 bps (0.02) spread, 92 days → payment = $51,111.11

**Post-2009 Standardization**
- Created commoditized market with central clearinghouse clearing
- Only two fixed "running" amounts: **1% or 5% per year**
- **Upfront payment** compensates for difference between swap premium and running standardized amounts
- Investment-grade debt: 1% running spread
- High-yield debt: 5% running spread

```
Quarterly swap premium payment =
  notional amount × running spread × (actual no. of days in quarter / 360)
```

**Running Spread Example (Investment-Grade)**
- $10M notional, 92 days, 2% agreed rate, 1% running spread (100 bps)
- Quarterly premium (running premium) = $10,000,000 × 0.01 × (92/360) = $25,555.56
- Protection buyer pays $25,555.56 per quarter with upfront payment to protection seller
- Upfront payment = PV of difference between 2% and 1% cash flows (using **ISDA Standard Upfront Model** supported by Markit Partners and Bloomberg)

**Running Spread Example (High-Yield)**
- $10M notional, 92 days, 4% agreed spread, 5% running spread (non-investment grade)
- Running premium = $10,000,000 × 0.05 × (92/360) = $127,777.78
- Protection seller agreed on 4%, not 5%—protection buyer pays 1% more per quarter than credit risk warrants
- Protection seller compensates protection buyer via upfront payment
- Upfront payment = PV of 1% of notional amount discounted by agreed-upon amount between buyer and seller

**Trade Execution Example**
- Alliance sold protection on XYZ Corp. to Goldman Sachs Asset Management (GSAM)
- JPMorgan acted as broker-dealer
- Alliance pays upfront amount plus proper initial amount to start/hold position
- GSAM receives upfront payment from Alliance via JPMorgan
- GSAM leaves some upfront payment with JPMorgan for initial derivative risk-based capital charge
- JPMorgan acts as intermediary (both parties demanded anonymity)

### Credit Event Settlement

**No Credit Event Scenario**
- Protection buyer continues quarterly swap payments over swap life based on running amount
- If credit event occurs, two outcomes:
  1. No further swap premium payments from protection buyer to seller
  2. **Termination value** determined for the swap

**Settlement Types**

**Physical Settlement**
- Protection buyer delivers specified face value amount of bonds to protection seller
- Protection seller pays protection buyer face value of bonds
- In real world (unlike hypothetical single-issue XYZ Corp.), all reference entities have many issues outstanding
- Multiple alternative issues = **deliverable obligations**
- Like Treasury bond/note futures (Chapter 29), protection buyer selects **cheapest-to-deliver** issue from deliverable obligations list
- Embedded option in physical settlement for single-name CDS

**Cash Settlement**
- All participants abide by results of auction process run by third-party provider involving multiple market participants
- Auction results bind all ISDA participants to payouts based on published results
- Lehman Brothers (2008) auction examples: 8.625% recovery; Fannie Mae senior debt 91.51%; Fannie Mae subordinated debt 99.90%; JCPenney unsubordinated debt recovery 0.125%

### Fixed Recovery CDS

- Alternative to standard CDS with physical settlement
- **Fixed recovery CDS**: eliminates uncertainty on recovery rate by fixing specific recovery value at time of trade
- If credit event triggered, protection seller makes cash settlement = 100 minus specified fixed recovery rate

### Auction Mechanism and ISDA Determinations Committee

**Auction Mechanism (2005)**
- **Markit** and **Creditex** introduced auction mechanism to determine fair price of defaulted reference entity
- Results published on www.creditfixings.com
- Auction determines final price for physical settlement of CDS contracts
- Inside midpoint = auction-identified price per unit of CDS
- Protection buyer receives from seller: difference between par value and auction-identified price per unit of contract's notional amount
- Example: Hertz Corporation CDS auction (June 24, 2020) = 26.375 based on 10 dealers

**ISDA Credit Derivatives Determination Committees**
- Critical role in CDS transactions
- Power to make binding decisions on: (1) whether credit event occurred, (2) which obligations of reference entity are deliverable, (3) whether auction will be held and its terms
- Final say on contractual interpretation
- Procedures set forth in **Determination Committee Rules**

### Central Clearing

**Post-2009 Regulatory Changes**
- Implementation of clearinghouses and exchanges for clearing CDS trades
- Addresses **systemic risk**: systemically important institutions filing for bankruptcy could leave counterparties at risk
- Failure of one important participant could destabilize financial system by inflicting significant losses on many trading partners simultaneously

**Pre-2009 Systemic Risk**
- 2008 reality: Lehman Brothers default and near defaults of AIG and Citigroup
- Both buyer and seller relied on counterparty to pay claims from CDS valuations changes—bilateral contract
- Now with clearinghouses: after two counterparties agree on CDS terms, they "clear" the CDS by having clearinghouse stand between them
- Clearinghouse acts as buyer of protection for one counterparty and seller of protection to the other


<!-- pp. 1161-1180 -->

## Credit Default Swaps (CDS) — Valuation and Applications

### CDS Clearinghouses

- Once swap is cleared, counterparties are insulated from each other's default risk and rely on clearinghouse performance
- With adequate capitalization, clearinghouses reduce systemic risk from large participant failures
- Similar to financial futures clearing operations — highly regulated and well-capitalized
- As of 2021, largest global CDS clearing houses: **ICE Clear Credit** and **London Common Exchange**

### Approximating Single-Name CDS Value

**Basis concept**: relationship between cash and derivatives markets — difference in spread between CDS and bonds of reference entity with similar maturities

**Normal state**: positive basis (CDS trades above corporate bond spread)
- Arbitrage with positive basis: sell the basis (sell cash bond, sell protection on same name)
- Arbitrage with negative basis: buy the basis (buy bond, buy protection on same name)

#### Eight Simplifying Assumptions for Valuation

1. Floating-rate debt obligation exists trading at par with maturity T, offering LIBOR + F
2. Coupon payment dates match payment dates to CDS protection seller
3. Borrowing to acquire floating-rate debt available at repo rate LIBOR + B (spread B applies to all participants)
4. Credit event occurs one day after coupon payment
5. CDS requires physical settlement; floating-rate debt is cheapest-to-deliver issue
6. No difficulty shorting bonds
7. No transaction costs
8. No counterparty risk for CDS or repo counterparty

#### Arbitrage Strategy for CDS Valuation

Strategy components:
- Buy floating-rate debt obligation with maturity T
- Fund purchase by borrowing for life of debt (also term T) in repo market
- Hedge credit risk by buying CDS with maturity T on reference entity

This creates a **default-free investment** (by Assumption 8, no counterparty risk)

**No credit event scenario**:
- Interest earned: LIBOR + F per period
- Borrowing cost: LIBOR + B per period
- Net cash flow: F − B

**Credit event scenario**:
- Physical delivery of floating-rate debt to CDS protection seller
- CDS proceeds repay repo loan
- Same payoff: F − B

**First approximation of CDS spread**: CDS spread S = F − B (difference between spread over LIBOR for issuing floating-rate debt vs. borrowing in repo market)

### Repo Rate and CDS Appeal

- Repo market offers multiple rates (overnight, term repo)
- Repo rates are short-term by nature; market participants cannot lock in fixed borrowing rate for several years
- **By entering CDS, participant effectively locks in borrowing rate for CDS term** — this is the appeal
- In practice, Assumption 1 rarely holds (corporate issuers as reference entities unlikely to have par floating-rate debt)

### Asset Swaps

**Asset swap**: allows investor to change cash flow characteristics of owned asset from fixed to floating or vice versa

Common structure: investor buys credit-risky fixed-rate bond and converts to floating rate via interest-rate swap with dealer
- If bond issuer defaults, investor still must make payments to swap dealer — still exposed to credit risk

**Example**: $10 million par 7.85% 5-year BBB bond at par + 5-year interest-rate swap
- Investor pays dealer 7.00% semiannually (fixed-rate payer)
- Dealer pays investor 6-month LIBOR
- Net received by investor: 0.85% + 6-month LIBOR

Result: investor converts fixed-rate BBB bond into synthetic floating-rate bond with spread of 85 bps over 6-month LIBOR

#### Par Asset Swap Structure

Typically combines:
- Sale of credit-risky bond to counterparty at par with no accrued interest
- Interest-rate swap

**Par asset swap**: If issuer defaults, swap transaction terminates and defaulted bonds returned to investor ± mark-to-market on swap transaction — investor still exposed to issuer's credit risk

**Asset swap spread**: coupon on bond in par asset swap paid in return for LIBOR + spread if necessary. This spread is the price of the asset swap, function of underlying bond's credit risk.

**Refined approximation for single-name CDS**: difference between asset swap spread (from par asset swap market) and spread over LIBOR in repo market

### CDS Implied Default Probabilities

**Early naive formula** (back out default probabilities from observed CDS spread):

```
Observed CDS spread in bps / 10,000 = (1 − Assumed recovery rate) × (Assumed default probability)
```

Solving for **implied default probability**:

```
Implied default probability = (Observed CDS spread in bps / 10,000) / (1 − assumed recovery rate)
```

**Example**: 500 bps 5-year CDS spread with 40% recovery rate:
- Implied default probability = (500/10,000) / (1 − 0.40) = 0.0833 = 8.33%

Higher recovery rate assumed → higher implied default probability for given CDS spread
- 60% recovery rate → 12.5% implied default probability

**Industry practice**: use standard fixed recovery rates depending on underlying
- Higher recovery rates assumed for loans vs. corporate bonds
- Higher recovery rates for municipal bonds vs. corporate debt

**Formula limitations** (recognized as CDS market matured):
- Only rough approximation of default probability
- Fails to account for bid-ask spread and counterparty risk
- Assumes recovery rate is correct and constant over time

**Modern approach**: more sophisticated models employ credit risk models from chapter 23. However, implied default probabilities are model-generated values with assumptions and estimated inputs. **Singh and Spackman** provide examples of misused default probabilities extracted from CDS spreads using industry standard fixed-recovery assumptions during distressed periods.

### Index CDS

**Index CDS**: written on standardized basket of reference entities, including:
- Corporate debt issuers
- Sovereign government issuers
- Municipal debt issuers
- Tranches of asset-backed securities
- Tranches of commercial mortgage-backed securities

**Mechanics differ from single-name CDS**: swap premium paid, but if credit event occurs, accrued payment to credit event date is paid, then swap premium payment **ceases** for single-name CDS. For index CDS, swap payment **continues** but quarterly premium payment is **reduced** (notional amount reduced due to removal of defaulted reference entity).

**Index rebalancing**: every six months, index provider creates new series
- Determines composition of reference entities
- Determines new premium level based on market liquidity, upgrades/downgrades, defaults
- Premium exchange timing: quarterly on/about March 20, June 20, September 20, December 20
- **Markit Group Ltd.** (London-based) administers the indexes

#### Index CDS on Corporate, Sovereign, and Municipal Debt

**North America corporate indexes** (most actively traded):
- **CDX.NA.IG** (North America Investment Grade): 125 investment-grade reference entities
- **CDX.NA.HY** (North America High Yield): 100 non-investment-grade reference entities
- **iTraxx Europe**: 125 corporate reference entities (European)
- All three use **equal weighting** of reference entities

Maturities: 3 to 10 years

**Credit events** differ by region:
- North American indexes: only bankruptcy and failure to pay (restructuring commonly excluded)
- iTraxx Europe: bankruptcy, failure to pay, and modified-modified restructuring

**Sovereign government indexes**:
- **iTraxx SovX CEEMEA Index**: 26 reference entities (Central/Eastern Europe, Middle East, Africa)
- **iTraxx SovX Asia Pacific Index**: 10 reference entities (Asia and Oceania)
- Both have 5-year and 10-year maturities, U.S. dollar currency

**Municipal index**:
- **MCDX**: 50 municipal entities from general obligation debt to revenue bonds (excludes tobacco and health care bonds)
- Must be BBB−(S&P), Baa3 (Moody's), or BBB−(Fitch) or above
- Not on negative watch

#### Index CDS on Tranches of ABS

**Subprime mortgage ABS**:
- **ABX.HE** index: 20 home equity loan deals from "top 20" issuers at time
- Typical subprime RMBS tranches: AAA, AA, A, BBB, BBB−
- **Five separate sub-indexes**: ABX.HE.AAA, ABX.HE.AA, ABX.HE.A, ABX.HE.BBB, ABX.HE.BBB−
- Position in sub-index = position in each of 20 tranches comprising the index

**Mechanics unique to ABX.HE**:
- Protection buyer makes swap payment **monthly** based on notional amount
- Notional amount declines over time due to tranche amortization
- Protection buyer receives payments for credit events (interest/principal shortfall, write-down)
- Unlike other index CDSs, under PAUG template a trigger event (write-down, interest shortfall) **may be reversed** in subsequent period — protection buyer would reimburse protection seller

#### Index CDS on Tranches of Commercial Mortgage-Backed Securities

- **CMBX** index: 25 CMBS transactions
- Sub-indexes based on tranche ratings (uses PAUG template as with ABX.HE)

#### Index CDS on Tranches of Corporate Entities

**Tranche CDS**: allows asset manager to obtain long or short credit exposure to particular portion of index loss

**Index tranche** defined by:
- **Attachment point**: minimum level of losses
- **Detachment point**: maximum level of losses

**CDX.IG.NA example** (100 names, six standardized tranches):
- 30%–100%: Super Senior
- 15%–30%: Senior
- 10%–15%: Upper Mezzanine
- 7%–10%: Mezzanine
- 3%–7%: Junior Mezzanine
- 0%–3%: Equity

**Equity tranche** (0%–3%): absorbs default of first 3% of reference entities
- Losses after 3% absorbed by Junior Mezzanine (up to 7%)
- Then Mezzanine realizes losses (7%–10%)
- Super Senior doesn't realize loss until index loss exceeds 30%

When credit event triggered:
- Appropriate tranche adjusted for reduced notional (based on **loss-given-default, LGD**)
- New detachment point calculated for remaining names in index

**Protection seller payout formula**:

```
Payout = (CDS notional amount × (1 − Recovery rate from auction) × Weighting) / Tranche size
```

**Weighting**: weighting of reference entity in index CDS
- Example: 100 entities in CDX.IG.NA → each is 1% weighting
- If credit event occurs for second entity → weighting becomes 1/99

**Tranche size** (tranche thickness): difference between attachment and detachment points

**Example**: Portfolio manager long CDS (sold protection, went long credit risk) in equity tranche for $10 million notional. One company defaults with $15 per $100 par recovery (ISDA/Creditfixings auction). Manager forced to pay $2,833,333.33:

```
Weighting = 1% = 0.01 (100 names in index)
CDS notional = $10,000,000
Recovery rate from auction = 15% = 0.15
Tranche size for equity = 3% − 0% = 3% = 0.03

Payout = ($10,000,000 × (1 − 0.15) × 0.01) / 0.03 = $2,833,333.33
```

**Leverage illustration**: If manager had gone long entire index (100% or 1 tranche), loss would have been only $85,000. Leverage determined by reciprocal of tranche size. Equity tranche size 0.03 → reciprocal 33.33 → leverage resulting in loss of 33.33 times $85,000.

### Economic Interpretation of CDS and Index CDS

#### Credit Protection Seller

**Economic position**: analogous to investor in cash bond (long position)

Cash flows for bond ABC investor:
- Cash outlay = bond ABC's price P₀
- Semiannual cash inflows = half of bond ABC's annual coupon
- Received as long as bond ABC doesn't default

If investor sells bond at time T: cash inflow = sale price P_T
- If adverse event occurred causing price to fall below purchase price (P_T < P₀): realizes loss = P_T − P₀

**CDS protection seller cash flows** (reference obligation bond ABC):
- Quarterly payment = fixed spread (1% or 5%)
- Cash inflow = quarterly swap payment
- Payments made only if entity ABC doesn't trigger credit event

Both positions receive periodic cash inflows as long as no adverse credit event stops payments.

**If credit event occurs**:
- Protection seller must make payment to protection buyer (cash outlay/loss)
- Bond investor realizes loss if adverse event occurs

**Economic position**: protection seller analogous to investor in cash bond (both long cash bond, both exposed to issuer's credit risk)

**Key funding difference**:
- Purchasing long position in bond requires payment = bond's purchase price
- Obtaining same credit risk exposure by selling protection via CDS **does not require cash outlay** — it's unfunded
- Obtaining exposure to bond by selling protection via CDS is a **leveraged position**

#### Credit Protection Buyer

**Economic position**: analogous to short position in cash bond

Cash flows for shorting bond ABC:
- Cash inflow = bond ABC's price P₀
- Semiannual cash outflows = half of bond ABC's annual coupon (reimbursing lender)
- Payments occur as long as bond ABC doesn't default

If investor buys bond ABC at time T to cover short: cash outflow = sale price P_T
- If adverse event occurred causing price to fall (P_T < P₀): realizes gain = P₀ − P_T

**CDS protection buyer cash flows** (reference obligation bond ABC):
- Quarterly payment (cash outflow) = quarterly swap payment
- Made only if bond ABC doesn't trigger credit event

Both positions have periodic cash outflows as long as no adverse credit event stops payments.

**If credit event occurs**:
- Protection buyer no longer makes payments to protection seller
- Receives payment if credit event occurs (analogous to gain from bond ABC price fall if adverse event)

**Economic position**: protection buyer analogous to short position in cash bond

### CDS Advantages Over Cash Bonds

**Two main advantages**:

1. **Leverage**: To buy (go long) credit via CDS, only pay (or receive) upfront amount + initial amount (requires much less capital than purchasing bond for cash)
   - Similar to purchasing call option — asset manager knows maximum loss on day 1
   - For CDS, most fund can lose is premium ± upfront amount
   - If corporate entity doesn't trigger credit event, manager can let trade mature or unwind early

2. **Ease of execution**: CDS much more efficient than selling bond short and borrowing in lending market

### Using CDS for Controlling Credit Risk

Portfolio managers use both single-name and index CDSs to control risk. Derivatives provide more transitionally efficient vehicle. Also potential to enhance return via relative value trades between cash and CDS markets.

#### Single-Name CDS Applications

**Obtaining exposure**: CDS market liquidity vs. corporate bond market makes it more efficient to obtain exposure to reference entity via CDS than cash market

**To obtain exposure** (long position): sell protection (be protection seller) — analogous to long position, easier in liquid CDS market

**Advantages over repo for leverage**:
1. **Fixed financing rate**: CDS provides fixed spread over LIBOR (repo rate spread can change)
2. **Permanent financing**: Repo is short-term and can be withdrawn on short notice; CDS provides embedded permanent financing for life of CDS
3. **100% financing**: Repo imposes haircut/margin; CDS offers 100% financing

**Shedding exposure**: Buy protection via single-name CDS

Why use CDS rather than selling bond in cash market?
- Less liquid corporate bond names may be difficult to sell at favorable prices when manager has credit concern
- Conditions may make selling difficult for portfolio manager

**Taking short position** (speculating on issuer difficulties):
- Would require shorting bond if permitted
- Shorting bonds in cash market sectors (other than Treasury) often difficult
- Equivalent position: entering CDS as protection buyer
- Can be done for entire sectors using index CDS

#### Index CDS Applications

**Adjusting credit exposure**:
- Gain credit exposure for standard basket by selling credit protection (sell protection = long credit risk)
- Reduce exposure for standard basket by buying credit protection (buy protection = short credit risk)
- Adjusting index CDS positions allows portfolio manager to alter credit exposure to bond market

**Particularly valuable for small bond portfolios**: Managing relative to bond index involves considerable idiosyncratic risk (all issues in broad-based index cannot be purchased given large number). One way to gain exposure to larger number of reference entities in bond sector comprising broad-based bond index is via index CDS.

**No leveraging if funds placed in cash**: If funds that would have purchased reference entities are placed in cash rather than used to purchase other reference entities, no leveraging need occur. Same point applies to interest-rate futures and swaps. If portfolio manager uses derivative for leveraging, this shows up in portfolio's key risk measures (duration for interest-rate futures/swaps, spread duration for CDSs).

### Key Points

- Interest-rate derivatives control interest-rate risk for changes in interest rate levels; credit derivatives control credit risk
- Most dominant credit derivative: **credit default swap (CDS)** — protection buyer makes swap premium payment to protection seller; protection buyer receives payment from seller only if credit event occurs
- CDS payments depend on triggering of credit event per **International Swaps and Derivatives Association** documentation
- Most controversial credit event: **restructuring**
- Special credit event definitions for CDSs written on ABS tranches (**pay-as-you-go definitions**)
- Single-name CDS: one reference entity/obligation written on corporate debt issuer (bonds/leverage loans), sovereign issuer, ABS security tranche, municipal bond issuer
- **Single-name CDS valuation approximation**: difference between asset swap spread (from par asset swap market) and spread over LIBOR in repo market
- **Asset swap** structured by dealer: investor selling fixed-rate credit-risky bond to dealer and receiving floating-rate payments
- CDS valuation model can obtain **implied default probability** for reference entity (probability depends on model validity and estimated inputs)
- **Index CDS**: written on standardized basket — corporate debt issuers, sovereign government issuers, municipal debt issuers, ABS tranches, CMBS tranches
- Unlike single-name CDS (contract terminates upon credit event triggering), index CDS swap payments continue if credit event triggered for one reference entity, but swap payments reduced due to lower notional amount (removal of defaulted entity from index)
- **Economic interpretation of credit protection seller**: analogous to leveraged position in reference entity (single-name CDS) or standardized basket (index CDS)
- **Economic interpretation of credit protection buyer**: analogous to short position in reference entity or reference entities
- Single-name CDSs can alter credit risk exposure of reference entity; typically, liquidity greater in CDS market than cash market, easier to short in CDS market
- Index CDS adjusts credit exposure of portfolio: increasing credit exposure by being protection seller, decreasing by being protection buyer

