## Appendix: The Investment Management Agreement

### IMA Structure and Purpose

- **Investment Management Agreement (IMA)**: Legal document governing services between bond portfolio management company and client (individual/organization)
- Sample agreement provides template for **separate account** management
- Client selects custodian; manager NOT authorized to accept cash/securities delivery or establish custodial arrangements

### Key IMA Sections

#### Appointment and Authority (Sections 1-2)
- Manager appointed to manage client's assets, sale proceeds, and income
- **Authority of Manager**: Authorized to supervise/direct investment without prior client approval, as agent and attorney-in-fact
- Manager can: buy/sell stocks/bonds/options/money market instruments (domestic and foreign); select brokers/dealers; execute documentation; purchase/sell/convert foreign currency at market rate
- Can engage external legal counsel for trade documentation review, charge account for costs

#### Guidelines and Instructions (Section 3)
- Investment objectives and restrictions detailed in **Exhibit A**
- Client can modify Guidelines or give specific Instructions anytime
- Modifications/Instructions NOT binding unless manager receives written notice from Authorized Person
- Manager has reasonable period to bring account into compliance with changes
- Manager under NO duty to investigate/verify Guidelines or Instructions
- Guidelines remain effective until canceled by subsequent written modifications

#### Fees (Section 4)
- **Quarterly fees** = one-fourth of annual rates in Exhibit B
- Based on account asset value on last NYSE trading day of quarter (**Valuation Date**)
- Initial billing begins at Inception Date (when agreement signed, funding received)
- Initial fee pro-rated from Inception Date through Valuation Date
- If manager serves less than full quarter: compensation determined on pro rata basis at termination date value
- Custodian automatically charges account and pays manager's fees upon invoice receipt

#### Representations and Warranties (Section 5)
- **(a) Client Assets**: Client sole owner; no transfer/sale restrictions; no liens/charges/encumbrances except those disclosed
- **(b) Authority**: Engagement doesn't violate constituent documents, material agreements, court orders, or applicable law; all investments duly authorized
- **(c) Form ADV**: Client acknowledges receipt of Part II; 48-hour right to terminate penalty-free if didn't receive ADV before execution (at risk for market fluctuations up to termination)
- **(d) Authorized Persons**: Officer signing on client's behalf (per Exhibit C) has full authority; client must promptly notify manager of changes affecting authority
- **(e) Notice of Certain Events**: Client must promptly notify if representations become inaccurate, false, misleading, or incomplete

#### Non-Exclusive Agreement (Section 6)
- Manager can engage in other business, manage other clients, provide services to other entities
- Manager may give different advice/take different actions for other clients vs. this account
- NO obligation to purchase/sell/recommend same securities manager or affiliates trade for own accounts
- Manager's recommendation ability may be **restricted by regulatory requirements or internal policies**
- Periods when manager cannot initiate certain transactions due to **aggregated position limits** reached
- Client NOT advised of these limitations

#### Liability of Manager (Section 7)
- Manager NOT liable for: (a) losses from good faith investment decisions made with prudent care/skill/diligence; (b) losses from compliance with Guidelines/Instructions believed accurate; (c) acts/failures of brokers/dealers; (d) circumstances beyond reasonable control (force majeure)
- **Force majeure** includes: acts of God, earthquakes, fires, floods, wars, terrorism, civil/military disturbances, sabotage, epidemics, riots, utility malfunctions, computer/transportation/communication failures, labor disputes, governmental actions, inability to obtain materials/equipment/transportation

#### Brokerage (Section 8)
- Manager authorized to consider broker/dealer research and services when selecting execution venues
- Can negotiate/assign **commission exceeding** another broker's rate if reasonable relative to brokerage/research services value
- **Aggregation/bunching**: Can aggregate orders across multiple client accounts managed by manager
- Allocation must NOT favor any account; executed at different prices allocated equitably among accounts
- Manager may receive various execution prices for full volume sold across all client accounts
- NOT obligated to average prices; may work to Account's disadvantage
- Manager/affiliates may restrict certain accounts from IPO purchases based on: trading strategies, account sizes, investment objectives/restrictions, expected secondary market premium
- NO obligation to effect transactions violating applicable laws/regulations or regulatory/self-regulatory body rules

#### Confidential Relationship (Section 9)
- All non-public confidential information treated in strictest confidence
- Disclosure permitted only: (a) by law/regulation/authority/judicial demand; (b) as set forth in Agreement; (c) with prior written approval
- Client authorizes manager to: (i) include client name in representative/sample lists (no contact info or holdings disclosed); (ii) use manager's experience with account in composite performance presentations/marketing materials/statistical compilations
- Such use does NOT disclose client identity beyond permitted extent

#### Reports (Section 10)
- **Written quarterly reports** of account as of Valuation Date
- Submitted within reasonable period following Valuation Date
- Foreign securities valued in USD unless otherwise agreed
- Client must examine reports promptly
- **60-day statute of limitations**: Upon 60 days after report OR agreement termination (whichever earlier), manager forever released from all liability/accountability except for acts/omissions client filed written objections about within 60 days
- Nothing impairs manager's right to judicial settlement of reports

#### Valuation (Section 11)
- **Listed securities** on exchanges or NASDAQ: last quoted sales price or official closing price on Valuation Date; if no reported sale, within range of most recent bid/ask
- **OTC securities**: within range of most recent bid/ask prices
- Securities trading both OTC and on exchange: valued according to broadest/most representative market as determined by manager
- **Illiquid/unreliable quotations**: security valued in good faith by manager to reflect fair market value

#### Proxies and Other Legal Notices (Section 12)
- **Proxy voting decisions** made by manager UNLESS expressly reserved by client
- Manager's voting obligation contingent on: (i) receiving proxies from custodian timely; (ii) lack of legal encumbrance to voting (securities lending programs)
- Manager NOT expected/required to take action re: lawsuits involving securities presently/formerly held or their issuers
- Manager will use **commercially reasonable efforts** to file proofs of claim in class-action lawsuits for securities held
- Can disclose account information in proofs of claim without prior permission/consent
- Manager may terminate filing service anytime; automatically terminates upon agreement termination
- Client acknowledges filing proof of claim may waive separate litigation rights
- Manager/affiliates may recommend litigation against issuer (opting out of class action or otherwise) on behalf of pooled investment vehicles advised by manager
- Manager will NOT provide notice/participation opportunity; client agrees to hold manager harmless
- Re: bankruptcies of securities issuers: Manager/affiliates may participate in bankruptcy proceedings and join creditors' committees for pooled vehicles advised by manager at sole discretion
- UNLESS otherwise agreed, manager NOT expected/required to file bankruptcy proofs of claim
- NOT responsible for failures to file or untimely filing if acting under authority granted; no responsibility for failure to file timely

#### Acknowledgment of Investment Risk (Section 13)
- Investment values may go down as well as up; NOT guaranteed
- Manager makes NO guarantees including specific performance levels
- Investment decisions subject to market/currency/economic/business risks; decisions not always profitable
- Past performance NOT indicative of future performance
- Securities/mutual funds/non-deposit investments NOT deposits, NOT guaranteed by manager/affiliates, NOT insured by FDIC/government agency; subject to investment risk including possible principal loss

#### Termination; Survival (Section 14)
- Either party can terminate on **30 days' written notice**
- Termination doesn't affect liabilities/obligations from transactions before termination
- **Sections 4, 7, 9, 10, 17, 18 survive termination**
- Upon termination: (a) liabilities from prior claims/matters survive with written notice; (b) manager can complete open transactions and retain sufficient amounts; (c) manager entitled to fees/expenses pro rated to termination date
- Client's exclusive responsibility to issue written instructions re: assets in account upon termination

#### Assignment (Section 15)
- Agreement may NOT be assigned by manager without client's prior written consent (per Investment Advisers Act of 1940)
- Manager may delegate duties to affiliates

#### Communications (Section 16)
- All reports/communications delivered in writing via: first-class mail, overnight courier, or confirmed facsimile (with original to follow)
- Parties may designate different addresses for receipt of reports/communications by written notice

#### Governing Law; Venue (Section 17)
- Governed by U.S. federal laws and state laws of [California] [New York]
- Jurisdiction/venue: federal and state courts in [State of California] [New York County, State of New York]

#### Entire Agreement; Modification (Section 18)
- Sets forth entire understanding of parties
- Supersedes all previous agreements/understandings/communications (oral or written)
- Can only be modified by specific written instrument executed by party against whom modification sought
- In conflicts between Agreement and non-incorporated instructions/investment guidelines/policy statements: Agreement controls

#### Additional Provisions (Sections 19-21)
- **Headings**: For convenience only; don't affect meaning/operation
- **Counterparts**: May be executed in any number; together constitute one instrument
- **Severability**: Invalid provisions void only to extent declared invalid; remaining provisions remain in full force

### Sample Agreement Exhibits

- **Exhibit A**: Statement of Investment Objectives; Statement of Client Account Restrictions (to be provided by client)
- **Exhibit B**: Fee Schedule (to be provided)
- **Exhibit C**: Certification of Authorized Persons (names, titles, specimen signatures)

### Chapter End Notes

**Coauthorship**: Chapter coauthored with **Fred Hoffman** (Assistant Professor in Practice of Finance, Rutgers University); grateful to **Gavan Nolan** (Director, IHS Markit, London) for helpful comments

**References to earlier content**:
1. Loan pricing off reference rate + spread; borrowers have option to set loan rate via CDS market (e.g., **Honeywell International** 2011: five-year, $2.8B credit line with such provision)
3. **Claire Boston and Sridhar Natarajan**, "Blackstone, Solus Settle Figure over Hovnanian CDS Trade," *Bloomberg News*, May 28, 2018
4. Corporate CDS vs. ABS CDS differences discussed in chapter 6 of **Laurie S. Goodman, Shumin Li, Douglas J. Lucas, Thomas A. Zimmerman, and Frank J. Fabozzi**, *Subprime Mortgage Credit Derivatives* (Hoboken, NJ: John Wiley & Sons, 2008)
6. **Markit (IHS Markit)**: Provides data/analytics for bond market participants; **Creditex** (wholly owned subsidiary of ICE) is interdealer broker for CDS and bonds
7. CDS valuation discussion: **Ren-Raw Chen, Frank J. Fabozzi, and Dominic O'Kane**, "The Valuation of Credit Default Swaps," in Frank J. Fabozzi (ed.), *Professional Perspectives on Fixed Income Portfolio Management*, vol. 4 (Hoboken, NJ: John Wiley & Sons, 2003), 255–280
8. Other pricing factors beyond credit (liquidity, counterparty risk): multiple *Journal of Fixed Income* articles cited (2010, 2011, 2012)
10. **Manmohan Singh and Carolyne Spackman**, "The Use (and Abuse) of CDS Spreads during Distress," International Monetary Fund, Working Paper WP/09/62, March 2009
11. **Basket default swaps**: Reference entities selected by counterparties (customized basket, unlike index CDS)
12. **iTraxx SovX Western Europe Index**: 15 reference entities from Eurozone + UK, Denmark, Norway, Sweden; little trading because EU banned "naked short" positions on sovereigns in 2012, making CDS trading in EU countries almost impossible
13. **Municipal CDS tax treatment**: Major factor influencing use as cash market substitute; interest on municipal bonds exempt from federal income tax, but swap spread received by protection seller NOT exempt per IRS (though IRS hasn't officially opined); disadvantage for tax-exempt municipal bond fund managers wanting sell protection alternative to owning bond; however, hedge fund managers (not concerned with tax treatment difference) use municipal CDS for other objectives

